00:08:10.120 --> 00:08:13.670
So my job here is to talk a bit
about the African background

00:08:13.670 --> 00:08:18.260
and the Transatlantic journeys
of the 1619, 20 and odd Negroes

00:08:18.260 --> 00:08:21.200
that arrived at Point
Comfort, Virginia.

00:08:21.200 --> 00:08:23.560
Point Comfort, which
is now Hampton.

00:08:23.560 --> 00:08:28.360
Right near the fledgling
Jamestown settlement in 1619.

00:08:28.360 --> 00:08:29.660
Who were they?

00:08:29.660 --> 00:08:31.970
Where did they come from?

00:08:31.970 --> 00:08:33.340
And what was their experience?

00:08:33.340 --> 00:08:35.610
What might their
experience have been as best

00:08:35.610 --> 00:08:38.750
as we can reconstruct it?

00:08:38.750 --> 00:08:43.450
In August 1619, a captive woman
named Angela, part of those 20

00:08:43.450 --> 00:08:50.140
and odd Africans that
landed at Point Comfort,

00:08:50.140 --> 00:08:59.190
arrived traumatized, mentally,
emotionally and physically,

00:08:59.190 --> 00:09:04.920
that endured a long journey
of months from their homes

00:09:04.920 --> 00:09:07.470
in West Central Africa.

00:09:07.470 --> 00:09:10.570
They likely came from the
West Central African states

00:09:10.570 --> 00:09:12.980
of Congo and Ndongo.

00:09:12.980 --> 00:09:16.370
If you take a look at
the map to the left here,

00:09:16.370 --> 00:09:19.470
you'll see this region
of West Central Africa,

00:09:19.470 --> 00:09:25.210
and you'll see Congo, and
you'll also see Ndongo

00:09:25.210 --> 00:09:26.510
in this area here.

00:09:26.510 --> 00:09:27.810
I hope everyone can see okay.

00:09:27.810 --> 00:09:32.750
And you'll also notice
the word Luanda,

00:09:32.750 --> 00:09:37.290
which will be the capital of a
Portuguese colony called Angola.

00:09:37.290 --> 00:09:40.640
So those are our three major
points that I'll refer to.

00:09:42.160 --> 00:09:46.810
Of course, the 1619 Africans
were not the first time

00:09:46.810 --> 00:09:48.940
that Africans had arrived
in the Western Hemisphere.

00:09:48.940 --> 00:09:54.090
By the time Angela and her
fellow captors had arrived,

00:09:54.090 --> 00:09:59.120
about 500,000 enslaved
Africans had already gone

00:09:59.120 --> 00:10:04.060
on a transatlantic journey
from the West Coast of Africa

00:10:04.060 --> 00:10:08.070
into the Americas, primarily in
Spanish colonies in the Americas

00:10:08.070 --> 00:10:11.080
and the Portuguese
colony of Brazil.

00:10:13.070 --> 00:10:16.960
They came from densely
settled urban towns.

00:10:16.960 --> 00:10:18.480
Some came from rural villages

00:10:18.480 --> 00:10:20.920
where they would have
raised agricultural crops

00:10:20.920 --> 00:10:23.200
like sorghum and millet.

00:10:23.200 --> 00:10:27.270
Some might have tended
livestock including cattle.

00:10:27.270 --> 00:10:31.380
And interestingly enough, if
you notice their names, Angela,

00:10:31.380 --> 00:10:37.170
Pedro, Peter, some featured
Iberian and Christian names.

00:10:37.170 --> 00:10:39.430
And that is indicative of
the fact that in this area,

00:10:39.430 --> 00:10:43.580
particularly in Congo, there had
been a longstanding engagement

00:10:43.580 --> 00:10:46.960
with Christianity
and with Portugal.

00:10:46.960 --> 00:10:49.350
Congo, in particular, was
a strong political state

00:10:49.350 --> 00:10:51.780
that maintained close
diplomatic, economic

00:10:51.780 --> 00:10:53.790
and cultural ties with Portugal.

00:10:53.790 --> 00:10:55.850
With Portuguese Catholic
missionaries and traders

00:10:55.850 --> 00:10:59.290
in Congo and Congolese
royal ambassadors

00:10:59.290 --> 00:11:02.300
and other emissaries
going to Portugal starting

00:11:02.300 --> 00:11:06.530
in the 15th century continuing
through the 16th century.

00:11:06.530 --> 00:11:09.660
By 1491, Congolese royalty
declared Christianity

00:11:09.660 --> 00:11:10.960
to be a state religion.

00:11:10.960 --> 00:11:12.690
But this was controlled
by the Congolese.

00:11:12.690 --> 00:11:15.990
So it's not an imposition
by the Portuguese,

00:11:15.990 --> 00:11:20.110
but this was Congolese engaging
in Christianity and using

00:11:20.110 --> 00:11:23.370
that to start Congolese-run
Christian schools.

00:11:23.370 --> 00:11:25.830
They were literate people

00:11:25.830 --> 00:11:27.730
who spoke the closely
related languages

00:11:27.730 --> 00:11:29.500
of Kikongo and Kimbundu.

00:11:29.500 --> 00:11:32.120
Some also spoke Portuguese.

00:11:32.120 --> 00:11:36.080
And by 1595, the papacy
in Rome had declared Congo

00:11:36.080 --> 00:11:38.680
to be its own Episcopal
district,

00:11:38.680 --> 00:11:43.110
and its primary church
became a cathedral.

00:11:43.110 --> 00:11:48.730
Christianity also impacted in
the state of Ndongo as well.

00:11:48.730 --> 00:11:51.810
So, the names are indicative

00:11:51.810 --> 00:11:55.360
of this engagement
with Christianity.

00:11:55.360 --> 00:11:58.980
Now, though Congo had
exported enslaved people

00:11:58.980 --> 00:12:01.840
to the African sugar-producing
island of South Tome

00:12:01.840 --> 00:12:04.250
and West Africa, island
off of West Africa

00:12:04.250 --> 00:12:08.040
and to Portugal itself,
since the early 16th century,

00:12:08.040 --> 00:12:12.160
Portuguese military expeditions
later in that same century

00:12:12.160 --> 00:12:15.480
against Ndongo and also Congo

00:12:15.480 --> 00:12:17.760
where the immediate
circumstances had generated

00:12:17.760 --> 00:12:22.660
thousands of enslaved war
captives including those

00:12:22.660 --> 00:12:25.040
that came in 1619.

00:12:25.040 --> 00:12:28.740
As I mentioned, Portugal had
established a small colony

00:12:28.740 --> 00:12:33.020
Angola in 1575, making
it the first African area

00:12:33.020 --> 00:12:36.940
under European occupation
during the early years

00:12:36.940 --> 00:12:39.110
of the Atlantic slave trade.

00:12:39.110 --> 00:12:42.470
And this trade, of course,
extends across the world,

00:12:42.470 --> 00:12:47.080
the transatlantic trade
from 1502 until 1870.

00:12:47.080 --> 00:12:51.080
This period of time when about
15 million Africans would have

00:12:51.080 --> 00:12:54.030
boarded ships, and about 12
million Africans would have

00:12:54.030 --> 00:12:57.180
arrived in the Americas.

00:12:57.180 --> 00:13:00.650
Why the disparity of 15
million leaving Africa

00:13:00.650 --> 00:13:04.990
and 12 million arriving
in the Americas?

00:13:04.990 --> 00:13:07.390
The middle passage, right.

00:13:07.390 --> 00:13:10.410
So an estimated 20 to 25%

00:13:10.410 --> 00:13:14.710
of those Africans boarding those
ships in Africa did not make it

00:13:14.710 --> 00:13:20.190
to the other side, Angela and
her fellow captives that arrived

00:13:20.190 --> 00:13:25.390
in Port Comfort with
those who survived.

00:13:25.390 --> 00:13:29.810
Now the Portuguese
dynamic is important here

00:13:29.810 --> 00:13:31.990
because Angola became
a launching point

00:13:31.990 --> 00:13:36.670
for Portuguese governors to
initiate war, specifically

00:13:36.670 --> 00:13:39.600
to generate war captives.

00:13:39.600 --> 00:13:42.970
Angolan-based Portuguese
merchants held the asiento,

00:13:42.970 --> 00:13:47.580
a contract with the Spanish
crown to deliver thousands

00:13:47.580 --> 00:13:52.820
of slaves, enslaved people I
should say, to Spanish colonies.

00:13:52.820 --> 00:13:56.940
So this combination of
policy, Portuguese policy,

00:13:56.940 --> 00:14:01.440
to engage in war and a
contract, a commercial contract,

00:14:01.440 --> 00:14:07.840
created a dynamic where
warfare was deliberately used

00:14:07.840 --> 00:14:11.700
to generate war captives
and enslaved people.

00:14:11.700 --> 00:14:15.610
And now 1619 Africans
were part of this dynamic.

00:14:15.610 --> 00:14:18.240
The Portuguese governor in 1617,

00:14:18.240 --> 00:14:24.380
Luis Mendes de Vasconcellos
Mendes was bent on conquests

00:14:24.380 --> 00:14:28.120
as the only means to get
the numbers that he wanted,

00:14:28.120 --> 00:14:31.490
an estimated 9,000
to 12,000 annually.

00:14:31.490 --> 00:14:36.340
In his reign from 1617 to 1621

00:14:36.340 --> 00:14:40.720
over 50,000 Africans were
exported from Luanda.

00:14:40.720 --> 00:14:45.240
Over 150 slave ships left
the Angolan port of Luanda,

00:14:45.240 --> 00:14:48.640
including our 1619 Africans.

00:14:48.640 --> 00:14:50.550
Now in contrast to
popular perceptions

00:14:50.550 --> 00:14:53.750
that African tribal wars were
the cause of slave trading,

00:14:53.750 --> 00:14:57.850
it was these military
expeditions of the Portuguese

00:14:57.850 --> 00:15:04.580
with mercenary militaristic
Africans known as the Imbangala

00:15:04.580 --> 00:15:08.380
that drove these chaotic
lawless conditions.

00:15:08.380 --> 00:15:11.670
In this war context then,
slavery became ubiquitous.

00:15:11.670 --> 00:15:13.910
Slave economies developed
as the buying and selling

00:15:13.910 --> 00:15:17.900
of enslaved people entered
African regional commercial

00:15:17.900 --> 00:15:22.780
networks and slaves, not silver
money, became the currency

00:15:22.780 --> 00:15:26.780
for all financial transactions
and for political tribute paid

00:15:26.780 --> 00:15:30.480
by lesser states to
more powerful states

00:15:30.480 --> 00:15:33.970
to whom they claimed
allegiance to.

00:15:35.230 --> 00:15:39.130
These enslaved Africans like
Angela, deeply traumatized

00:15:39.130 --> 00:15:41.730
by the circumstances
of their enslavement,

00:15:41.730 --> 00:15:43.850
their forced separation
from family and friends

00:15:43.850 --> 00:15:46.830
and the stripping of
their societal identities.

00:15:46.830 --> 00:15:52.170
Imagine, all of who you are,
connected to all the people

00:15:52.170 --> 00:15:55.470
that you love, no
longer matters.

00:15:55.470 --> 00:15:57.440
That you are reduced,
dehumanized,

00:15:57.440 --> 00:15:59.080
to be a unit of labor.

00:15:59.080 --> 00:16:04.830
Imagine then that at
the point of capture,

00:16:04.830 --> 00:16:07.150
which could be hundreds
of miles in the interior,

00:16:07.150 --> 00:16:08.520
you are already starting a type

00:16:08.520 --> 00:16:13.720
of middle passage even before
you step foot on a ship.

00:16:13.720 --> 00:16:16.970
Because quite often, the point
of capture during this point

00:16:16.970 --> 00:16:18.280
of the Atlantic slave
trade could be

00:16:18.280 --> 00:16:19.840
in the interior of Africa.

00:16:19.840 --> 00:16:22.860
And you could be marched to the
coast over hundreds of miles

00:16:22.860 --> 00:16:25.430
and be sold over and over again

00:16:25.430 --> 00:16:27.330
with different owners before
you even get to a ship.

00:16:27.330 --> 00:16:31.250
And then imagine Angela and
her fellow captives boarding

00:16:31.250 --> 00:16:35.940
that ship and being in the
holds of these slave ships.

00:16:35.940 --> 00:16:42.860
And perhaps being
raped, women, children

00:16:42.860 --> 00:16:45.750
and sometimes men, raped.

00:16:45.750 --> 00:16:50.890
Imagine being chained to the
holds where there is nowhere

00:16:50.890 --> 00:16:53.150
to go to the bathroom.

00:16:53.150 --> 00:16:56.120
Imagine for the first
time being on an ocean.

00:16:56.120 --> 00:16:59.100
Many Africans had never seen the
ocean much less been on a ship.

00:16:59.100 --> 00:17:02.420
And dealing with the seasickness
that comes with that and having

00:17:02.420 --> 00:17:05.770
to wallow in your
excrement and your vomit.

00:17:05.770 --> 00:17:08.470
And dealing with a disease
that runs rampant in the holds.

00:17:08.470 --> 00:17:11.230
Dysentery was a major killer.

00:17:11.230 --> 00:17:14.010
And in the age of wind and
sail, when you had to rely

00:17:14.010 --> 00:17:17.560
on the winds and the currents
to make it across the ocean,

00:17:17.560 --> 00:17:18.860
that journey could take months.

00:17:18.860 --> 00:17:20.720
And you could run out of food.

00:17:20.720 --> 00:17:25.100
And already in a weakened state,
if you are perceived to be one

00:17:25.100 --> 00:17:27.180
of the diseased or one of
the ones who are too weak

00:17:27.180 --> 00:17:30.290
to make it across, you'd
be thrown overboard

00:17:30.290 --> 00:17:31.590
where the sharks
that had learned

00:17:31.590 --> 00:17:36.610
to follow these ships
would eat you.

00:17:38.420 --> 00:17:41.470
Imagine that experience for
Angela and her fellow captives

00:17:41.470 --> 00:17:44.620
that might have dealt
with some of this.

00:17:44.620 --> 00:17:50.070
We do know that Angela was one
of 350 enslaved people loaded

00:17:50.070 --> 00:17:55.230
onto the San Juan Bautista,
a Portuguese slaving ship,

00:17:55.230 --> 00:17:58.680
leaving Luanda, bound
for the Spanish colony

00:17:58.680 --> 00:18:01.480
in Veracruz, Mexico.

00:18:01.480 --> 00:18:08.150
That was supplying the
numbers needed in that asiento.

00:18:08.150 --> 00:18:10.380
In Veracruz, they would
have joined a growing slave

00:18:10.380 --> 00:18:12.540
population that included
plantation workers

00:18:12.540 --> 00:18:14.240
and personal servants.

00:18:14.240 --> 00:18:21.060
But, they didn't make it
to Veracruz, as we know.

00:18:21.060 --> 00:18:22.520
They made it to Point Comfort.

00:18:22.520 --> 00:18:24.220
So what happened?

00:18:24.220 --> 00:18:27.520
In route to Veracruz, the
San Juan Bautista stopped

00:18:27.520 --> 00:18:29.950
in Jamaica, selling 24 children.

00:18:29.950 --> 00:18:34.250
And there were many
children on these voyages.

00:18:34.250 --> 00:18:36.590
And they were exchanged
for needed supplies.

00:18:36.590 --> 00:18:40.910
Perhaps the San Juan Bautista
was running low on supplies.

00:18:40.910 --> 00:18:43.750
Now just a few days
away from Mexico,

00:18:43.750 --> 00:18:47.990
the San Juan Bautista
was boarded

00:18:47.990 --> 00:18:51.520
by two English privateers,
The White Lion,

00:18:51.520 --> 00:18:54.650
The White Lion was carrying
a Dutch license to wage war

00:18:54.650 --> 00:18:59.620
on the pirate ships,
and The Treasurer.

00:18:59.620 --> 00:19:02.940
And those two ships took cargo
off of the San Juan Bautista

00:19:02.940 --> 00:19:06.270
and about 60 enslaved people
with them, including Angela

00:19:06.270 --> 00:19:09.920
and our 20 and odd
Negroes, or Africans.

00:19:09.920 --> 00:19:16.200
In late August 1619,
the White Lion arrived

00:19:16.200 --> 00:19:17.500
in the Virginia settlement

00:19:17.500 --> 00:19:20.990
that was encroaching upon
Native American territories.

00:19:20.990 --> 00:19:24.380
Trading their 20 and odd
Negroes for victuals.

00:19:24.380 --> 00:19:28.650
This is the [inaudible]
record food.

00:19:28.650 --> 00:19:32.460
Angela and approximately 28
other captive Africans arrived

00:19:32.460 --> 00:19:36.330
on The Treasurer four days
later after The White Lion.

00:19:36.330 --> 00:19:39.140
But The Treasurer had sailed
on to a second English colony

00:19:39.140 --> 00:19:43.700
of Bermuda, where most were
sold, including Angela.

00:19:43.700 --> 00:19:46.280
But in February 1620,
Angela and a handful

00:19:46.280 --> 00:19:47.810
of other original captives

00:19:47.810 --> 00:19:51.060
from the San Juan Bautista found
themselves once again boarding

00:19:51.060 --> 00:19:55.070
The Treasurer where they
landed back in Virginia.

00:19:55.070 --> 00:19:56.430
And she and her fellow captives

00:19:56.430 --> 00:19:59.490
from West Central Africa
were most, if not all,

00:19:59.490 --> 00:20:06.990
of the 32 Africans recorded
in Virginia's May 1620 census.

00:20:08.210 --> 00:20:17.680
As I conclude, passing
through Imbangala, Portuguese,

00:20:17.680 --> 00:20:20.650
Dutch and English hands,
the experience of Angela

00:20:20.650 --> 00:20:23.900
and her fellow captives
foreshadowed major themes

00:20:23.900 --> 00:20:26.520
in Africa and the
Atlantic world.

00:20:26.520 --> 00:20:29.510
The Portuguese colony of Angola
reflected an early example

00:20:29.510 --> 00:20:32.750
of intensifying slave
rating and slavery in Africa

00:20:32.750 --> 00:20:35.380
and deepening European
economic interests

00:20:35.380 --> 00:20:38.730
that would lead indirectly
to European colonialism,

00:20:38.730 --> 00:20:43.370
of virtually all of Africa,
nearly three centuries later.

00:20:43.370 --> 00:20:48.270
Luanda, the port from
which Angela and the 20

00:20:48.270 --> 00:20:52.440
and odd Africans came
would be the export site

00:20:52.440 --> 00:20:55.300
for 1.3 million other captives

00:20:55.300 --> 00:20:58.370
over the entire Atlantic
slave trade period.

00:20:58.370 --> 00:21:01.730
More than any other
African port.

00:21:01.730 --> 00:21:04.230
Angela's story also
provides a glimpse

00:21:04.230 --> 00:21:08.040
of the increased Atlantic world
presence of not just the Spanish

00:21:08.040 --> 00:21:10.450
and the Portuguese, but
particularly of the Dutch

00:21:10.450 --> 00:21:12.390
and the English and
the soon to be French

00:21:12.390 --> 00:21:15.930
who are moving beyond
just pirating Portuguese

00:21:15.930 --> 00:21:20.300
and Spanish ships for their
riches gained from slavery,

00:21:20.300 --> 00:21:22.090
but to establish
their own colonies

00:21:22.090 --> 00:21:23.580
in the Western Hemisphere.

00:21:23.580 --> 00:21:27.510
And Jamestown was part
of that early effort.

00:21:27.510 --> 00:21:31.130
England would be the
largest slave trading nation

00:21:31.130 --> 00:21:32.940
in the 18th century.

00:21:32.940 --> 00:21:36.760
To these erstwhile pirates
and aspirant colonists,

00:21:36.760 --> 00:21:39.130
Angela and other enslaved
people would be critical

00:21:39.130 --> 00:21:44.550
in generating untold
wealth for new societies

00:21:44.550 --> 00:21:48.790
that were race-based, that
developed racial caste systems,

00:21:48.790 --> 00:21:52.330
echoes of which we
still live with today.

00:21:52.330 --> 00:21:53.670
Despite common perceptions

00:21:53.670 --> 00:21:55.820
that enslaved Africans
came almost exclusively

00:21:55.820 --> 00:21:58.970
from West Africa, and many did,

00:21:58.970 --> 00:22:01.960
Angela's story illuminates
the fact that most

00:22:01.960 --> 00:22:06.680
of the 500,000 African women,
men and children that arrived

00:22:06.680 --> 00:22:11.450
in the Americas by 1619 came
from West Central Africa.

00:22:11.450 --> 00:22:13.810
It was these West Central
Africans like Angela

00:22:13.810 --> 00:22:15.110
that were the chartered
generations,

00:22:15.110 --> 00:22:16.410
those first generations
of Africans

00:22:16.410 --> 00:22:17.710
and the largest force
migration in world history

00:22:17.710 --> 00:22:19.010
that laid the foundation
for the African diaspora

00:22:19.010 --> 00:22:20.310
and the Americas.

00:22:20.310 --> 00:22:22.110
Thank you for listening.

00:22:22.110 --> 00:22:35.500
[ Applause ]

00:22:40.470 --> 00:22:42.770
&gt;&gt; Cassandra Newby-Alexander:
Good afternoon.

00:22:44.900 --> 00:22:50.900
My colleague has beautifully
laid out the foundation.

00:22:50.900 --> 00:22:54.800
And I'm going to talk about
the rest of the story.

00:22:54.800 --> 00:22:59.610
I'm going to take
you, not from the West

00:22:59.610 --> 00:23:04.110
or Central African coastlines,
but rather to Virginia,

00:23:04.110 --> 00:23:08.900
to the first place
where America began.

00:23:08.900 --> 00:23:13.100
That beginning in 1619
with the arrival of the 20

00:23:13.100 --> 00:23:17.230
and odd Negroes aboard the
English ship White Lion,

00:23:17.230 --> 00:23:21.150
people of African descent
became a permanent cultural

00:23:21.150 --> 00:23:23.440
and political fixture
in America.

00:23:23.440 --> 00:23:28.060
For the first century, the vast
majority of the Africans coming

00:23:28.060 --> 00:23:32.850
to Virginia were from
Central and West Africa.

00:23:32.850 --> 00:23:36.650
Subjected to a kind of
forced acculturation

00:23:36.650 --> 00:23:39.190
that accompanied
their enslavement,

00:23:39.190 --> 00:23:42.790
Africans adapted over time.

00:23:42.790 --> 00:23:46.620
This, however, did not imply
that they divested themselves

00:23:46.620 --> 00:23:48.580
of their African culture.

00:23:48.580 --> 00:23:54.830
Instead, they infused America's
evolving customs with art,

00:23:54.830 --> 00:24:00.160
music, culinary practices,
trading systems, agricultural

00:24:00.160 --> 00:24:03.860
and architectural
techniques and language,

00:24:03.860 --> 00:24:09.220
creating a creole society
that became the foundation

00:24:09.220 --> 00:24:12.400
of an emerging American culture.

00:24:12.400 --> 00:24:14.840
And though initially
small in number,

00:24:14.840 --> 00:24:21.160
these first-generation Africans
helped define even the concepts

00:24:21.160 --> 00:24:25.730
of freedom and liberty
because of their ongoing demand

00:24:25.730 --> 00:24:29.080
for inclusion and civil rights.

00:24:29.080 --> 00:24:34.280
Through this effort, they helped
establish an international

00:24:34.280 --> 00:24:36.630
definition of freedom.

00:24:36.630 --> 00:24:42.300
Indeed, as the past 400
years will attest, Africans

00:24:42.300 --> 00:24:46.030
and their descendants
embarked on a quest

00:24:46.030 --> 00:24:50.400
to restore their humanity
and to be recognized

00:24:50.400 --> 00:24:53.760
as true American citizens.

00:24:53.760 --> 00:24:57.270
After Africans began arriving
in the Virginia colony,

00:24:57.270 --> 00:25:01.140
many of the English officials
became these first owners

00:25:01.140 --> 00:25:02.810
of these people.

00:25:02.810 --> 00:25:06.100
Their plantations, as
you can see on this map

00:25:06.100 --> 00:25:12.040
that is a map created by Smith

00:25:12.040 --> 00:25:14.140
in the early part
of the 17th century.

00:25:14.140 --> 00:25:17.200
And I want you to pay attention
to this because this kind

00:25:17.200 --> 00:25:23.740
of takes our vantage point,
our viewpoint, and changes it.

00:25:23.740 --> 00:25:25.040
It shifts it.

00:25:25.040 --> 00:25:26.490
Our viewpoint is like this.

00:25:26.490 --> 00:25:29.670
But the map takes it
and moves it that way.

00:25:29.670 --> 00:25:31.470
Because when you
see the Chesapeake,

00:25:31.470 --> 00:25:34.160
the Chesapeake is
usually, in our maps,

00:25:34.160 --> 00:25:36.410
depicted almost north and south.

00:25:36.410 --> 00:25:39.450
But this one actually
moves it almost

00:25:39.450 --> 00:25:42.590
to an east-west direction.

00:25:42.590 --> 00:25:46.350
And that is because that
was the vantage point

00:25:46.350 --> 00:25:48.290
of the first people.

00:25:48.290 --> 00:25:50.830
It shows their trade
and their connections.

00:25:50.830 --> 00:25:54.860
And that's why the first
Africans, when they arrived,

00:25:54.860 --> 00:25:59.310
the English when they arrived,
the settled on the same lands

00:25:59.310 --> 00:26:02.910
and oriented themselves
in the same way as many

00:26:02.910 --> 00:26:05.990
of the Native peoples
who established the towns

00:26:05.990 --> 00:26:09.200
and cities in Virginia.

00:26:09.200 --> 00:26:13.830
So these plantations that the
English gravitated towards

00:26:13.830 --> 00:26:18.510
and created for themselves
were located on one of the 18

00:26:18.510 --> 00:26:22.930
to 19 prime sites, so
along the James River.

00:26:22.930 --> 00:26:28.200
Starting between
April of 1619 and 120,

00:26:28.200 --> 00:26:32.940
the early Africans were
concentrated in these areas,

00:26:32.940 --> 00:26:36.720
James City, Elizabeth City
and Suri [phonetic] Counties.

00:26:36.720 --> 00:26:41.130
In these early years,
the Africans who appeared

00:26:41.130 --> 00:26:45.260
in the records typically were
listed along with their owners

00:26:45.260 --> 00:26:50.160
and often with only a first
name, belying their status

00:26:50.160 --> 00:26:55.210
in the colony, even during these
critical foundational years.

00:26:55.210 --> 00:27:00.650
According to the Virginia
muster records of 1624, 1625,

00:27:00.650 --> 00:27:04.740
21 Africans lived in
the colonized area

00:27:04.740 --> 00:27:07.070
of Abraham Percy's plantation,

00:27:07.070 --> 00:27:11.190
now known as Flowerdew
Plantation or Flowerdew Hundred.

00:27:11.190 --> 00:27:15.450
Only four out of the 11 people
mentioned were mentioned

00:27:15.450 --> 00:27:16.750
by name.

00:27:16.750 --> 00:27:20.590
So the rest of the people
didn't even have an identity

00:27:20.590 --> 00:27:22.630
as a human being.

00:27:22.630 --> 00:27:26.830
Well, those four people
included Anthony, Williams,

00:27:26.830 --> 00:27:29.710
John and another Anthony.

00:27:29.710 --> 00:27:33.660
If you notice, they lacked
a last name, a surname,

00:27:33.660 --> 00:27:36.750
a name that would
give them civil rights

00:27:36.750 --> 00:27:40.400
because it would recognize
them as human beings.

00:27:40.400 --> 00:27:45.990
In the township of Jamestown,
there were three Africans

00:27:45.990 --> 00:27:49.490
who were listed with
only one listed by name,

00:27:49.490 --> 00:27:52.370
and that name was misspelled.

00:27:52.370 --> 00:27:58.130
The woman's name was Angela, and
yet, they listed her as Angelo.

00:27:58.130 --> 00:28:02.120
Angela was the first
African woman documented.

00:28:02.120 --> 00:28:05.140
She was forcibly brought
into the Virginia colony,

00:28:05.140 --> 00:28:08.640
as you heard earlier, on
this ship, The Treasurer.

00:28:08.640 --> 00:28:13.630
She was listed as the property
of Captain William Pierce.

00:28:13.630 --> 00:28:15.610
She was referred to as quote,

00:28:15.610 --> 00:28:20.170
that Negro woman
who raised pigs.

00:28:20.170 --> 00:28:24.680
Angela was probably working
with Pierce's wife, Joan,

00:28:24.680 --> 00:28:28.730
to maintain a three
two four-acre garden.

00:28:28.730 --> 00:28:33.060
Another Angolan brought into
the colony was named Edward.

00:28:33.060 --> 00:28:35.200
Identified as living

00:28:35.200 --> 00:28:38.350
on a plantation called
Necoland [phonetic].

00:28:38.350 --> 00:28:41.580
The owner was Richard Kingsmill.

00:28:41.580 --> 00:28:47.370
Four other Angolans lived on
the Bennett Plantation, Peter,

00:28:47.370 --> 00:28:50.990
Anthony, Francis and Margaret.

00:28:50.990 --> 00:28:54.650
While two others lived
at Elizabeth City,

00:28:54.650 --> 00:28:58.680
which is now Hampton, with
Captain William Tucker.

00:28:58.680 --> 00:29:02.160
And their names,
Anthony and Isabella.

00:29:02.160 --> 00:29:04.980
And reportedly, Anthony
and Isabella

00:29:04.980 --> 00:29:09.640
who were married has a child
in 1624 that they named

00:29:09.640 --> 00:29:13.380
after Captain William
Tucker, who interestingly,

00:29:13.380 --> 00:29:17.110
became the child's godfather,

00:29:17.110 --> 00:29:20.560
thereby protecting
that child's status.

00:29:20.560 --> 00:29:25.240
Francis Payne was enslaved by
William Eltonhead [phonetic],

00:29:25.240 --> 00:29:29.540
but by 1655, he was
listed as a free man

00:29:29.540 --> 00:29:32.080
with a wife and children.

00:29:32.080 --> 00:29:36.440
And he actually owned
land on Cherrystone Creek,

00:29:36.440 --> 00:29:39.190
located on the eastern shore.

00:29:39.190 --> 00:29:41.780
Emmanuel Drigues
[phonetic] or Rodrigues,

00:29:41.780 --> 00:29:47.830
was listed as the property of
Captain Francis Pott in 1645.

00:29:47.830 --> 00:29:50.960
And while it is unclear
when he became free,

00:29:50.960 --> 00:29:53.570
he was part of a
minority of Africans

00:29:53.570 --> 00:29:58.080
who gained their freedom,
securing 145 acres of land

00:29:58.080 --> 00:30:03.230
on the eastern shore on King's
Creek in North Hampton County.

00:30:03.230 --> 00:30:06.400
Similarly, William
Harmon, who was transported

00:30:06.400 --> 00:30:09.880
to the Virginia colony
and enslaved in 1662

00:30:09.880 --> 00:30:12.960
to William Kendall in North
Hampton County, again,

00:30:12.960 --> 00:30:18.070
on the eastern shore, was
freed six years later in 1668,

00:30:18.070 --> 00:30:21.640
and he was listed in the
records along with is wife,

00:30:21.640 --> 00:30:26.550
who interestingly, was listed
with both a first and last name,

00:30:26.550 --> 00:30:28.070
Jane Gossell [phonetic].

00:30:28.070 --> 00:30:33.210
And he was listed as raising
cattle on the eastern shore.

00:30:33.210 --> 00:30:37.720
So while there were some whose
status changed from enslaved

00:30:37.720 --> 00:30:42.870
to free, the vast majority of
these early Africans were locked

00:30:42.870 --> 00:30:45.630
in a system of perpetual
servitude

00:30:45.630 --> 00:30:49.900
within the American
colonies' first slaving zone.

00:30:49.900 --> 00:30:53.590
Even so, Africans
successfully adapted their labor

00:30:53.590 --> 00:30:57.320
and [inaudible] and traditions
to this new environment

00:30:57.320 --> 00:30:58.690
with responsibilities

00:30:58.690 --> 00:31:02.480
that included agricultural
production, cooking,

00:31:02.480 --> 00:31:05.440
construction and
household management.

00:31:05.440 --> 00:31:08.690
It was during these early
years that African food

00:31:08.690 --> 00:31:11.720
and culinary practices
were incorporated

00:31:11.720 --> 00:31:13.400
into the Virginia colony.

00:31:13.400 --> 00:31:18.110
For example, the Virginia house
was an adapted architectural

00:31:18.110 --> 00:31:21.290
model that English
colonists began constructing,

00:31:21.290 --> 00:31:24.770
similar to the shotgun houses
you see commonly in the South.

00:31:24.770 --> 00:31:29.490
Unlike the English houses that
were designed to retain heat

00:31:29.490 --> 00:31:32.010
and limit airflow
throughout the house,

00:31:32.010 --> 00:31:34.220
the Virginia houses
were constructed

00:31:34.220 --> 00:31:37.800
to do just the opposite
because of the warm temperatures

00:31:37.800 --> 00:31:40.250
and the humid environment.

00:31:40.250 --> 00:31:44.080
In early Virginia, northern
Native American foods

00:31:44.080 --> 00:31:47.870
such as corn, squash, pumpkin
and beans, were integrated

00:31:47.870 --> 00:31:49.770
into the English diet.

00:31:49.770 --> 00:31:53.590
These foods intersected
with the culinary traditions

00:31:53.590 --> 00:31:57.200
that the English introduced
into America that included pigs

00:31:57.200 --> 00:32:02.840
and cattle, chicken and sheep,
wheat, flour, onions, carrots

00:32:02.840 --> 00:32:06.000
and a variety of
greens and beans.

00:32:06.000 --> 00:32:09.380
They also introduced sweet
potatoes and white potatoes

00:32:09.380 --> 00:32:14.390
to the colonies through
this Atlantic trade.

00:32:14.390 --> 00:32:17.620
When the Africans were brought
into the American colonies,

00:32:17.620 --> 00:32:20.840
many of their native plants
accompanied them aboard these

00:32:20.840 --> 00:32:26.910
ships, including black-eyed
peas, okra, yams, peanuts,

00:32:26.910 --> 00:32:29.410
watermelons, sesame
seeds, cassava,

00:32:29.410 --> 00:32:32.890
kola nuts, and lima beans.

00:32:32.890 --> 00:32:35.790
And because Africans were
brought into the colonies

00:32:35.790 --> 00:32:38.630
and lived and worked in
the households of some

00:32:38.630 --> 00:32:42.640
of the most prominent planters,
the same planters, by the way,

00:32:42.640 --> 00:32:46.680
responsible for transporting
supplies into the colony

00:32:46.680 --> 00:32:50.930
and establishing the cultural
tone, they were tasked

00:32:50.930 --> 00:32:52.710
with these cooking duties.

00:32:52.710 --> 00:32:56.600
Historian Donna Gabaccia
argued, and I quote,

00:32:56.600 --> 00:33:01.220
"It was African slaves'
central position as producers

00:33:01.220 --> 00:33:04.810
and processors of
food that allowed them

00:33:04.810 --> 00:33:08.150
to leave their own
special mark."

00:33:08.150 --> 00:33:11.970
It was in the Central
and West African areas,

00:33:11.970 --> 00:33:14.680
or I should say it was the
Central and West Africans

00:33:14.680 --> 00:33:16.890
who laid the foundations
for the cuisine

00:33:16.890 --> 00:33:20.120
that we know today
as southern cooking.

00:33:20.120 --> 00:33:24.670
Which infused dishes with hot
pepper and spices, millet,

00:33:24.670 --> 00:33:27.070
peanuts and sweet potatoes.

00:33:27.070 --> 00:33:31.950
For example, as they
mixed fried okra with rice

00:33:31.950 --> 00:33:35.000
and black-eyed peas using
slow cooking techniques

00:33:35.000 --> 00:33:38.320
to produce dishes like
gumbo and peanut soup,

00:33:38.320 --> 00:33:42.990
their African culinary practices
altered the way the English

00:33:42.990 --> 00:33:45.860
and Native Americans
consumed food.

00:33:45.860 --> 00:33:48.780
Culinary Historian
Jessica Harris observed

00:33:48.780 --> 00:33:53.010
that food traditions
provide a historical roadmap

00:33:53.010 --> 00:33:54.860
for American society.

00:33:54.860 --> 00:33:59.030
Because the foods we eat
hold symbols and meaning

00:33:59.030 --> 00:34:04.260
that connects us with our ethnic
origins and shared creole past.

00:34:04.260 --> 00:34:08.130
America's colonial cookbooks
reflected the creolization

00:34:08.130 --> 00:34:12.540
of foods and food ways
while simultaneously erasing

00:34:12.540 --> 00:34:16.080
or making invisible the
contributions of the people

00:34:16.080 --> 00:34:19.710
who created those food ways
and customs to begin with.

00:34:19.710 --> 00:34:23.790
Scholar Alisha Cromwell noted
that the challenge, therefore,

00:34:23.790 --> 00:34:31.320
is "studying the silences"
of how Africans contributed

00:34:31.320 --> 00:34:34.880
to the evolution of
American culture.

00:34:34.880 --> 00:34:39.130
Religious expression of
these 17th century Africans,

00:34:39.130 --> 00:34:43.600
as Rebecca Goetz's 2012
groundbreaking work,

00:34:43.600 --> 00:34:47.630
The Baptism of Early
Virginia noted, how Africans

00:34:47.630 --> 00:34:50.670
in Virginia used
religion as the vehicle

00:34:50.670 --> 00:34:52.820
by which they individually

00:34:52.820 --> 00:34:56.470
and collectively
expressed their voice.

00:34:56.470 --> 00:35:01.600
During the colonial period,
many sought to retain elements

00:35:01.600 --> 00:35:05.280
of their African customs and
manners to the frustration

00:35:05.280 --> 00:35:08.710
of whites who regarded
their refusal to assimilate

00:35:08.710 --> 00:35:13.230
as indicators of their
heathenism and inferiority.

00:35:13.230 --> 00:35:17.480
Yet, these 17th century Africans
came armed with the knowledge

00:35:17.480 --> 00:35:21.440
of ecclesiastical and
theological rules called

00:35:21.440 --> 00:35:23.490
from their knowledge
of Catholicism

00:35:23.490 --> 00:35:26.000
because of their contact
with the Portuguese.

00:35:26.000 --> 00:35:28.830
For a short period,
Africans were even able

00:35:28.830 --> 00:35:33.320
to use baptism practices and
the legal protections that came

00:35:33.320 --> 00:35:37.790
from godparents as pathways
to freedom and a way

00:35:37.790 --> 00:35:40.280
to build community networks.

00:35:40.280 --> 00:35:44.680
Thus, the American colonial
period was replete with examples

00:35:44.680 --> 00:35:49.250
of how Africans infused their
various cultural practices

00:35:49.250 --> 00:35:51.310
into the overall culture

00:35:51.310 --> 00:35:55.350
that was evolving during these
early years, impacting everyone,

00:35:55.350 --> 00:35:58.110
not just those within
their community,

00:35:58.110 --> 00:36:04.250
but the entire community of
Virginia and later of America.

00:36:04.250 --> 00:36:10.420
Religion, music, food ways,
customs, oral traditions,

00:36:10.420 --> 00:36:17.800
language and art became uniquely
American because of the African.

00:36:17.800 --> 00:36:20.820
Patent jubah [phonetic] which
was the beating of the hands

00:36:20.820 --> 00:36:23.640
on the thighs and the stomping
of the heels of the feet

00:36:23.640 --> 00:36:26.200
to produce percussion music.

00:36:26.200 --> 00:36:30.590
Fiddle and banjo music became
the traditional entertainment

00:36:30.590 --> 00:36:34.470
forms among Africans
and African-Americans.

00:36:34.470 --> 00:36:38.420
And because these individuals
were the primary musicians,

00:36:38.420 --> 00:36:44.150
especially in Virginia, they
impacted the way that everyone

00:36:44.150 --> 00:36:48.470
in the colony and later
in the nation saw music,

00:36:48.470 --> 00:36:51.960
heard music, felt music.

00:36:51.960 --> 00:36:57.480
These kinds of musical
practices were the most popular

00:36:57.480 --> 00:37:00.230
and most highly in demand.

00:37:00.230 --> 00:37:03.560
The intersection of
countless African ethnicities

00:37:03.560 --> 00:37:06.280
through the transatlantic
slave trade journey

00:37:06.280 --> 00:37:10.500
and in the American crucible
created a new form of culture

00:37:10.500 --> 00:37:13.630
that combined these
traditions with those

00:37:13.630 --> 00:37:16.160
of the English and
Native peoples.

00:37:16.160 --> 00:37:18.650
And while these new
practices and traditions

00:37:18.650 --> 00:37:20.940
that were influenced
so effectively

00:37:20.940 --> 00:37:25.230
by primarily these enslaved
Africans that culture

00:37:25.230 --> 00:37:30.240
as African-American novelist
Ralph Ellison noted was,

00:37:30.240 --> 00:37:33.730
"more than the sum of
this brutalization."

00:37:33.730 --> 00:37:38.570
Instead, acknowledging
the impact of Africans

00:37:38.570 --> 00:37:42.720
in the formation of American's
culture, is an affirmation

00:37:42.720 --> 00:37:46.540
of life and the attitudes
of those who became part

00:37:46.540 --> 00:37:48.860
of the American experience.

00:37:48.860 --> 00:37:52.400
And for those Africans
in American, the infusion

00:37:52.400 --> 00:37:56.540
of their cultures into the
American landscape while

00:37:56.540 --> 00:37:59.270
assimilating and
acculturating meant

00:37:59.270 --> 00:38:04.550
that they were an important
part of transforming, mutating

00:38:04.550 --> 00:38:08.480
and even creating a
unique hybrid culture

00:38:08.480 --> 00:38:11.150
that we call American.

00:38:11.150 --> 00:38:12.950
Thank you.

00:38:12.950 --> 00:38:19.500
[ Applause ]

00:38:26.430 --> 00:38:28.470
&gt;&gt; Lynette Lewis Allston:
First, thank you to Dr. Braxton

00:38:28.470 --> 00:38:30.850
and to the Library of
Congress for allowing me

00:38:30.850 --> 00:38:37.330
to give you all the Native
perspective on early Virginia.

00:38:37.330 --> 00:38:42.840
From the arrival of the English
in 1607 until the 1619 arrival

00:38:42.840 --> 00:38:47.070
of Africans and European women,
the world of the Native people

00:38:47.070 --> 00:38:50.010
of Virginia was drastically
altered.

00:38:50.010 --> 00:38:54.270
The clash of cultures brought
disruption of lifestyle,

00:38:54.270 --> 00:38:57.230
loss of oral tradition
and language,

00:38:57.230 --> 00:39:00.220
assault of manifest
destiny on spiritual

00:39:00.220 --> 00:39:02.540
and religious practices,

00:39:02.540 --> 00:39:06.450
resulting in prejudice
and death.

00:39:06.450 --> 00:39:10.420
The challenge in explaining
how the Native population felt

00:39:10.420 --> 00:39:12.110
about the arrival
of new people is

00:39:12.110 --> 00:39:16.690
to make my 21st century
unselfish view of living

00:39:16.690 --> 00:39:18.290
in the early 17th century

00:39:18.290 --> 00:39:22.520
because Native people
transferred information

00:39:22.520 --> 00:39:25.840
from generation to generation
through oral tradition.

00:39:25.840 --> 00:39:30.810
Much of that information
has been lost.

00:39:30.810 --> 00:39:34.740
The sources of written
accounts from early times

00:39:34.740 --> 00:39:37.960
in Virginia are found
in personal writings

00:39:37.960 --> 00:39:41.760
such as diaries and in the
collection of statutes and laws

00:39:41.760 --> 00:39:45.650
that were created by those
who arrived at Jamestown.

00:39:45.650 --> 00:39:48.610
Through time, much has been
written about the early times

00:39:48.610 --> 00:39:54.050
in Virginia by people who
have offered their analysis

00:39:54.050 --> 00:39:56.310
and perspective,
their speculation

00:39:56.310 --> 00:40:00.630
and their imagination to address
their views of the events.

00:40:00.630 --> 00:40:05.480
In most cases, the people who
wrote about life in Jamestown

00:40:05.480 --> 00:40:10.210
in the 17th century were not
altruistic in their accounts.

00:40:10.210 --> 00:40:15.210
They were people who had
more to gain than to give.

00:40:15.210 --> 00:40:17.800
Was the first reaction
by the Native tribes

00:40:17.800 --> 00:40:20.600
that these newcomers
are here to harm?

00:40:20.600 --> 00:40:24.270
Did their curiosity
about the first Europeans

00:40:24.270 --> 00:40:27.790
and then Africans overcome fear?

00:40:27.790 --> 00:40:31.970
Long before 1619, indigenous
communities were accustomed

00:40:31.970 --> 00:40:35.520
to the arrival of
persons from far away.

00:40:35.520 --> 00:40:38.190
Usually, these travelers
were indigenous people

00:40:38.190 --> 00:40:41.070
from other locales coming
for trade, and they were

00:40:41.070 --> 00:40:43.430
of similar skin color.

00:40:43.430 --> 00:40:46.040
They spoke languages that
at least some words could

00:40:46.040 --> 00:40:47.940
be understood.

00:40:47.940 --> 00:40:53.320
They came, they socialized,
they traded, and they left

00:40:53.320 --> 00:40:55.870
to come again another time.

00:40:55.870 --> 00:41:00.510
These new visitors who came
by ships looked different,

00:41:00.510 --> 00:41:03.570
spoke an unknown
language and brought

00:41:03.570 --> 00:41:06.620
with them curiously
different goods.

00:41:06.620 --> 00:41:10.610
Were they like the others
here to trade and depart?

00:41:10.610 --> 00:41:13.140
Or did they have a
different motive?

00:41:13.140 --> 00:41:15.590
In short order, it became
obvious that this group

00:41:15.590 --> 00:41:17.800
of strangers who brought
no women with them

00:41:17.800 --> 00:41:19.500
in the first phase
were different

00:41:19.500 --> 00:41:21.490
from previous visitors.

00:41:21.490 --> 00:41:25.980
Native curiosity was tempered
by an awareness of danger

00:41:25.980 --> 00:41:28.280
and soon turned to unease.

00:41:28.280 --> 00:41:32.440
Unease turned to fear, and
fear turned to loathing.

00:41:32.440 --> 00:41:38.510
By 1619, the reality of
conflict was a part of living

00:41:38.510 --> 00:41:41.460
with the presence of people
who exhibited cultural biases

00:41:41.460 --> 00:41:46.030
and invasive socioeconomic
goals.

00:41:46.030 --> 00:41:48.450
Within a short time of
arriving in Jamestown,

00:41:48.450 --> 00:41:51.310
the colonists were engaged
in the cycle of attacks

00:41:51.310 --> 00:41:55.820
and reprisals by the paladin
tribes who saw the reality

00:41:55.820 --> 00:41:59.590
that the arrival of these
new people was an invasion.

00:41:59.590 --> 00:42:03.910
Just 12 years after the arrival
of the strangers in 1607,

00:42:03.910 --> 00:42:07.860
the tribes saw the coming
of more unfamiliar arrivals,

00:42:07.860 --> 00:42:11.930
Africans, and finally
a few European women.

00:42:11.930 --> 00:42:14.890
The attack on the Native
population was not only

00:42:14.890 --> 00:42:17.040
physically with weapons
and disease,

00:42:17.040 --> 00:42:21.630
there was also a cultural
attack with religion, education,

00:42:21.630 --> 00:42:24.480
gender roles, forced
apprenticeships

00:42:24.480 --> 00:42:29.290
on Native children, forced
indenture, slavery and loss

00:42:29.290 --> 00:42:32.600
of identity through
paper genocide.

00:42:32.600 --> 00:42:36.340
With the establishment of the
colonial government in 1619

00:42:36.340 --> 00:42:39.760
and the meeting of the House
of Burgesses, the direction

00:42:39.760 --> 00:42:45.390
for defining race and
class and separation began.

00:42:45.390 --> 00:42:48.590
Statutes at large, laws of
Virginia began the process

00:42:48.590 --> 00:42:51.950
of creating barriers and
restrictions on those

00:42:51.950 --> 00:42:56.960
who were viewed by Angelo
men as being subordinate.

00:42:56.960 --> 00:43:00.310
This new societal strata
enhanced the evolution

00:43:00.310 --> 00:43:04.220
of interaction between
Native people, Africans,

00:43:04.220 --> 00:43:07.130
women and the indentured
population.

00:43:07.130 --> 00:43:09.350
Some of that interaction
was natural

00:43:09.350 --> 00:43:12.620
and voluntary, and
some was coerced.

00:43:12.620 --> 00:43:16.250
The laws of Virginia show that
English mindset towards Natives

00:43:16.250 --> 00:43:19.910
with citations, even
in the index of laws

00:43:19.910 --> 00:43:28.470
that created references that
say savages, "see Indians."

00:43:28.470 --> 00:43:32.020
The threat of quasi
slavery was ever present.

00:43:32.020 --> 00:43:34.490
In 1655, there's
a law that states

00:43:34.490 --> 00:43:38.890
if Indian parents bring their
children in as hostages,

00:43:38.890 --> 00:43:44.410
then choose the persons to
care for their children.

00:43:44.410 --> 00:43:47.460
They will not be used as slaves.

00:43:47.460 --> 00:43:51.720
But we will do our best to bring
them into Christianity, civility

00:43:51.720 --> 00:43:54.320
and the knowledge
of necessary trades.

00:43:54.320 --> 00:43:58.290
Now this may sound like a
benevolent idea, but in reality,

00:43:58.290 --> 00:44:00.310
it is a method of acculturation.

00:44:00.310 --> 00:44:07.860
Also, in 1655, it was deemed "a
great scandal to Christianity,

00:44:07.860 --> 00:44:11.880
rendering religion
contemptable to buy an Indian.

00:44:11.880 --> 00:44:15.740
Yet, selling an Indian, who
had committed an infraction,

00:44:15.740 --> 00:44:17.250
was acceptable.

00:44:17.250 --> 00:44:21.350
As stated in a 1660 decision
that resulted from an accusation

00:44:21.350 --> 00:44:25.700
of damages done on English
property and states if they,

00:44:25.700 --> 00:44:30.310
the Indians, do not comply then
so many as the court think fit,

00:44:30.310 --> 00:44:32.940
shall be apprehended and sold

00:44:32.940 --> 00:44:36.960
into a foreign country
to satisfy the award.

00:44:36.960 --> 00:44:39.540
Through a series of
violent confrontations,

00:44:39.540 --> 00:44:42.920
subsequent documents that the
colonial government labeled

00:44:42.920 --> 00:44:47.850
as treaties, traditional Native
cultural patterns of trade,

00:44:47.850 --> 00:44:52.150
travel and even selection of
leadership, was transformed.

00:44:52.150 --> 00:44:53.740
Methods were instituted

00:44:53.740 --> 00:44:58.190
to control traditional
indigenous leadership structure.

00:44:58.190 --> 00:45:02.390
We read historical documents
which label various Natives

00:45:02.390 --> 00:45:05.900
as chiefs, queens, kings,
headmen, without realizing

00:45:05.900 --> 00:45:09.750
that title terms were
generated by the colonists.

00:45:09.750 --> 00:45:11.970
As an example, in 1663,

00:45:11.970 --> 00:45:16.290
the colonial statute stated the
Indians shall not have the power

00:45:16.290 --> 00:45:18.070
within themselves to elect

00:45:18.070 --> 00:45:21.720
or constitute their
own chief commander.

00:45:21.720 --> 00:45:23.670
But the present honorable
governor

00:45:23.670 --> 00:45:27.530
and his successors shall
authorize such person.

00:45:27.530 --> 00:45:34.270
By the time of Nathanial Bacon's
oddly-named rebellion in 1676,

00:45:34.270 --> 00:45:38.340
those who fought could keep
a captured Native as a reward

00:45:38.340 --> 00:45:41.800
for assisting and
attacking the Occaneechi.

00:45:41.800 --> 00:45:43.660
Field historians
have acknowledged

00:45:43.660 --> 00:45:47.410
that Nathanial Bacon's primary
objective was to disrupt one

00:45:47.410 --> 00:45:50.990
of the largest pre-Anglo
trading centers near present-day

00:45:50.990 --> 00:45:53.230
Clarksville, Virginia.

00:45:53.230 --> 00:45:57.070
By decimating the Occaneechi,
Bacon was positioning himself

00:45:57.070 --> 00:46:02.000
and other Anglos to control
a major historical indigenous

00:46:02.000 --> 00:46:03.960
trade route.

00:46:03.960 --> 00:46:07.880
Accurate history is filled
with unpleasant realities.

00:46:07.880 --> 00:46:11.880
And I acknowledge this because
a segment of my own tribe,

00:46:11.880 --> 00:46:13.940
the Nottoway, assisted Bacon

00:46:13.940 --> 00:46:17.060
in the slaughter
of the Occaneechis.

00:46:17.060 --> 00:46:20.480
If we seek historical
reconciliation, we must be open

00:46:20.480 --> 00:46:25.610
to addressing immoral
ambiguity and unpleasantries.

00:46:25.610 --> 00:46:29.700
There was an ongoing and
everchanging list of early laws

00:46:29.700 --> 00:46:33.280
on anti-miscegenation, birth
of mixed-race children,

00:46:33.280 --> 00:46:36.040
trade with Natives,
Natives traveling

00:46:36.040 --> 00:46:41.510
through land appropriate
by colonists and more.

00:46:41.510 --> 00:46:46.200
The most obvious and sensitive
issue is disparate consideration

00:46:46.200 --> 00:46:48.670
of racial intermarriage.

00:46:48.670 --> 00:46:51.010
The way we looked,
the visual appearance

00:46:51.010 --> 00:46:54.380
of the Native population, had
much to do with the attraction

00:46:54.380 --> 00:46:57.620
for interaction between
Natives and Africans.

00:46:57.620 --> 00:46:59.670
An example of appearances
provided

00:46:59.670 --> 00:47:03.480
in the 1700s diary
of William Bird.

00:47:03.480 --> 00:47:06.780
Bird visited the Nottoway
great town during his travels

00:47:06.780 --> 00:47:11.500
to survey the border between
Virginia and North Carolina.

00:47:11.500 --> 00:47:16.030
Bird described the Nottoway
as people of mahogany skins

00:47:16.030 --> 00:47:20.300
and the copper colored
ones of Nottoway town.

00:47:20.300 --> 00:47:24.650
He described the Nottoway this
way long before an extensive

00:47:24.650 --> 00:47:29.400
intermarriage with Nottoway with
either Europeans or Africans.

00:47:29.400 --> 00:47:31.630
Over time, the Nottoway
did intermarry

00:47:31.630 --> 00:47:34.210
with Europeans and Africans.

00:47:34.210 --> 00:47:37.430
We can assume that there
was an inclination of people

00:47:37.430 --> 00:47:41.890
of darker skin tones who
were viewed and had to act,

00:47:41.890 --> 00:47:43.660
and were acted upon
as subordinate

00:47:43.660 --> 00:47:48.390
to establish common bonds
for safety and survival.

00:47:48.390 --> 00:47:51.300
To that end, the
Nottoway tribe who lived

00:47:51.300 --> 00:47:55.230
in the 1700s were
living on 40,000 acres

00:47:55.230 --> 00:47:58.820
of reservation land,
provided safe haven

00:47:58.820 --> 00:48:02.520
for segments of displaced
tribes.

00:48:02.520 --> 00:48:05.400
Escaped slaves and
runaway indentures,

00:48:05.400 --> 00:48:09.200
also found save haven
on that reservation.

00:48:09.200 --> 00:48:12.000
At the time that Bird was
surveying the Virginia North

00:48:12.000 --> 00:48:15.700
Carolina dividing line, the
Weyanoke Tribe had been removed

00:48:15.700 --> 00:48:18.740
from its territory
from the James River.

00:48:18.740 --> 00:48:22.730
In a deposition of Henry
Briggs in 1711, Briggs states

00:48:22.730 --> 00:48:24.630
that the Weyanoke live
on Wyocake [phonetic]

00:48:24.630 --> 00:48:29.540
on the Nottoway River and have
paid the Nottoway much peak

00:48:29.540 --> 00:48:30.840
to live there.

00:48:30.840 --> 00:48:33.490
At the same time,
segments of other tribes,

00:48:33.490 --> 00:48:36.510
including Meherrin,
Nansemond and Tuscarora came

00:48:36.510 --> 00:48:38.630
to live with the Nottoway.

00:48:38.630 --> 00:48:41.640
The Nottoway 40,000-acre
reservation was a buffer

00:48:41.640 --> 00:48:44.520
against Anglo conflicts
with the Tuscarora

00:48:44.520 --> 00:48:46.800
who were stridently resistant

00:48:46.800 --> 00:48:49.810
to colonial usurpation
of their land.

00:48:49.810 --> 00:48:53.380
The Nottoway reservation was
in present day South Hampton

00:48:53.380 --> 00:48:55.660
and Sussex County in Virginia.

00:48:55.660 --> 00:49:00.770
With the loss of territory,
some Virginia natives were able

00:49:00.770 --> 00:49:03.040
to survive by living
on reservation,

00:49:03.040 --> 00:49:06.050
and others became servants
and laborers on land

00:49:06.050 --> 00:49:08.370
that was once their own.

00:49:08.370 --> 00:49:11.230
In the 19th century, the
Nottoway took allotments

00:49:11.230 --> 00:49:14.560
of reservation land and
became individual landowners.

00:49:14.560 --> 00:49:18.450
Yet, as individual landowners,
we were subject to taxes.

00:49:18.450 --> 00:49:22.180
And if we did not pay those
taxes, we were subject

00:49:22.180 --> 00:49:24.980
to involuntary indenture.

00:49:24.980 --> 00:49:29.610
1619 was the pinnacle
marker for racial

00:49:29.610 --> 00:49:32.790
and gender discrimination
laws that compounded

00:49:32.790 --> 00:49:38.060
and impacted Native identity
into the 20th century.

00:49:38.060 --> 00:49:42.430
Native people traditionally had
a balanced view of gender roles

00:49:42.430 --> 00:49:44.360
and the importance of women.

00:49:44.360 --> 00:49:45.660
Native women were involved

00:49:45.660 --> 00:49:48.710
as decision makers
in tribal structure.

00:49:48.710 --> 00:49:52.160
As time passed, Native
identity was transitioned

00:49:52.160 --> 00:49:56.070
to other designations
based on skin color.

00:49:56.070 --> 00:50:00.620
In Virginia, paper genocide
systematically categorized

00:50:00.620 --> 00:50:04.630
Natives as people of color
and erased Native identity

00:50:04.630 --> 00:50:07.810
on census records
and legal documents.

00:50:07.810 --> 00:50:12.010
The Racial Integrity Act of
1924 in its implementation

00:50:12.010 --> 00:50:15.800
by Walter Plecker as head of
the Bureau of Vital Statistics

00:50:15.800 --> 00:50:19.700
for Virginia mandated that
there were only two races

00:50:19.700 --> 00:50:23.160
in Virginia, white and colored.

00:50:23.160 --> 00:50:28.430
The Racial Integrity
Act remained until 1967,

00:50:28.430 --> 00:50:30.440
when the US Supreme
Court in Loving

00:50:30.440 --> 00:50:35.250
versus Virginia found the law
prohibiting interracial marriage

00:50:35.250 --> 00:50:37.220
to be unconstitutional.

00:50:37.220 --> 00:50:42.350
A subsequent change in
Virginia law restored identity

00:50:42.350 --> 00:50:44.370
and allowed birth certificates

00:50:44.370 --> 00:50:48.760
of Virginia tribal
members to be corrected.

00:50:48.760 --> 00:50:53.640
In today's world, I remind
citizens of my tribe,

00:50:53.640 --> 00:50:57.230
including one that's sitting
on the front row over here,

00:50:57.230 --> 00:51:00.830
that the Nottoway
Indian Tribe of Virginia,

00:51:01.960 --> 00:51:06.090
that our first family
were Native people.

00:51:06.090 --> 00:51:10.110
And that anyone else who
came along simply joined us,

00:51:10.110 --> 00:51:12.970
and that made us
who we are today.

00:51:12.970 --> 00:51:14.770
Thank you.

