00:53:16.480 --> 00:53:21.590
Red Black Spirit Medicine.

00:53:21.590 --> 00:53:30.510
This story is personal and at
the same time representative

00:53:30.510 --> 00:53:36.870
of the spiritual journey of
many persons of mixed triracial

00:53:36.870 --> 00:53:39.980
or red-black heritage.

00:53:39.980 --> 00:53:43.180
Perhaps for me, it
begins in my childhood

00:53:43.180 --> 00:53:46.180
in Prince George's
County, Maryland.

00:53:46.180 --> 00:53:51.400
On the banks of a stream
that fed the Anacostia River.

00:53:51.400 --> 00:53:54.350
Long before I ever thought
about being a scholar

00:53:54.350 --> 00:53:57.420
of African-American
literature and culture.

00:53:57.420 --> 00:54:05.720
When I was a child, we lived
in a house in the woods just

00:54:05.720 --> 00:54:08.970
on the banks of Indian Creek.

00:54:08.970 --> 00:54:11.930
The boundary between our black

00:54:11.930 --> 00:54:17.430
and mixed-race community
and another world.

00:54:17.430 --> 00:54:21.320
A world that was largely white.

00:54:21.320 --> 00:54:24.040
But throughout this region

00:54:24.040 --> 00:54:29.430
in the time before there was a
beltway, there were communities

00:54:29.430 --> 00:54:37.110
like ours with tightly
interwoven kinship relations.

00:54:37.110 --> 00:54:41.860
My father taught me how
to cup my hands to drink

00:54:41.860 --> 00:54:46.560
from a metal bucket
or clear spring.

00:54:46.560 --> 00:54:54.190
How to set traps for rabbits
and how to find the North Star.

00:54:54.190 --> 00:55:00.500
The older men moved like shadows
in and out of the forest,

00:55:00.500 --> 00:55:07.940
emerging with squirrel, rabbits
and occasionally other game.

00:55:08.980 --> 00:55:15.310
I roamed the woods and wetlands,
watchful for water moccasins

00:55:15.310 --> 00:55:19.420
and dangerous sinkholes.

00:55:19.420 --> 00:55:24.500
We farmed the land
growing corn, beans,

00:55:24.500 --> 00:55:28.330
squash and occasionally melon.

00:55:28.330 --> 00:55:31.850
We caught and cooked the
eels from Indian Creek,

00:55:31.850 --> 00:55:38.870
frying them up in hot grease to
eat with hominy and succotash.

00:55:38.870 --> 00:55:45.190
In the spring, my father's
mother would prepare a physic

00:55:45.190 --> 00:55:50.570
of pokeweed, a poisonous
plant that I learned

00:55:50.570 --> 00:55:56.960
to pick before its
purple berries formed.

00:55:56.960 --> 00:56:00.550
And Dad would head down
into Southern Maryland

00:56:00.550 --> 00:56:03.850
with my mother's Gus
and butler cousins

00:56:03.850 --> 00:56:07.210
for the spring herring run.

00:56:07.210 --> 00:56:11.590
Dad and Cousin Amos Gus
caught lots of herring,

00:56:11.590 --> 00:56:17.670
and they salted them down
and preserved in a barrel.

00:56:17.670 --> 00:56:23.410
Only later did I learn that the
food practices of my family,

00:56:23.410 --> 00:56:26.930
such as the salting of
herring and the growing

00:56:26.930 --> 00:56:31.980
of the three sisters
were tangible signs

00:56:31.980 --> 00:56:38.480
of the cultural interaction
of red and black people.

00:56:39.910 --> 00:56:43.690
My mother's mother
was a red-brown woman

00:56:43.690 --> 00:56:50.880
who could heal ailments
with plants from the forest.

00:56:50.880 --> 00:56:54.490
This she learned from
her grandmother, Nana,

00:56:54.490 --> 00:57:00.230
who as my grandmother told
me, had long black hair,

00:57:00.230 --> 00:57:02.980
hair long enough to sit on.

00:57:02.980 --> 00:57:05.420
From my paternal grandmother,

00:57:05.420 --> 00:57:10.330
I learned about my great-great
grandfather Peyton Harrison,

00:57:10.330 --> 00:57:15.710
Black and Indian who
came up from Virginia.

00:57:15.710 --> 00:57:20.490
He told my grandmother
that his people were some

00:57:20.490 --> 00:57:24.090
of the Jamestown Africans.

00:57:25.450 --> 00:57:30.270
Sometimes, as I roam
through the woods or dug clay

00:57:30.270 --> 00:57:36.040
from the stream bank, I did
wonder where the Indians

00:57:36.040 --> 00:57:41.530
for whom Indian Creek
was named had gone.

00:57:41.530 --> 00:57:44.710
But then my mind would
return to the present

00:57:44.710 --> 00:57:50.260
and the pending threat of
integration, which had not

00:57:50.260 --> 00:57:56.170
yet occurred but
was looming over us.

00:57:56.170 --> 00:57:58.420
In those days, colored children

00:57:58.420 --> 00:58:02.040
from Southern Prince George's
County came all the way

00:58:02.040 --> 00:58:08.110
up into Lakeland to attend
our Colored Lakeland School.

00:58:08.110 --> 00:58:13.570
No one was black back then.

00:58:13.570 --> 00:58:20.060
We were all Colored with a
capital C. Call somebody Black,

00:58:20.060 --> 00:58:24.080
you're going to start a fight.

00:58:24.080 --> 00:58:26.320
Those proctored [phonetic]
children,

00:58:26.320 --> 00:58:29.170
they didn't associate
with us much.

00:58:29.170 --> 00:58:33.220
We thought they were strange
with their straight hair

00:58:33.220 --> 00:58:37.070
and their standoff ways.

00:58:37.070 --> 00:58:39.150
Only recently did
I learn that many

00:58:39.150 --> 00:58:41.330
of the proctors now
self-identify

00:58:41.330 --> 00:58:43.830
as Piscataway Indians.

00:58:43.830 --> 00:58:47.520
And only when urban renewal
conspired to take what I thought

00:58:47.520 --> 00:58:52.600
of our land there on
Indian Creek did I begin

00:58:52.600 --> 00:58:58.500
to appreciate the convergence
of things I had seen

00:58:58.500 --> 00:59:02.500
and the stories I had heard.

00:59:02.500 --> 00:59:07.240
It was these stories of my
ancestors in the Chesapeake

00:59:07.240 --> 00:59:12.180
that fueled my desire to
learn more about the Weyanoke,

00:59:12.180 --> 00:59:17.280
both as a scholar and as
a symbolic descendant.

00:59:17.280 --> 00:59:24.250
In time, I learned that Weyanoke
is at once a people, a place

00:59:24.250 --> 00:59:31.070
or places and incorporated
association and ritual ground

00:59:31.070 --> 00:59:36.070
where the collective historical
trauma of colonialism.

00:59:36.070 --> 00:59:40.290
The enslavement of black and
Native people and the trauma

00:59:40.290 --> 00:59:45.740
of separation and
exclusion gets repaired

00:59:45.740 --> 00:59:50.870
through collective
healing prayers, music,

00:59:50.870 --> 00:59:54.340
ritual and the intentional
coming together

00:59:54.340 --> 01:00:00.910
of persons prepared to
celebrate red-black connections.

01:00:00.910 --> 01:00:07.440
The name Weyanoke itself means
sassafras, a medicinal tree used

01:00:07.440 --> 01:00:08.780
for healing purposes

01:00:08.780 --> 01:00:14.390
by indigenous people
transported Africans

01:00:14.390 --> 01:00:18.310
and European colonists alike.

01:00:18.310 --> 01:00:23.170
And today, the Weyanoke
Association is first

01:00:23.170 --> 01:00:27.480
and foremost a site of healing.

01:00:30.050 --> 01:00:34.170
The Chesapeake or Great
Shellfish Bay was the site

01:00:34.170 --> 01:00:37.490
of the Weyanoke Plantation
in Virginia,

01:00:37.490 --> 01:00:40.640
where the first Africans in
the English Americas lived

01:00:40.640 --> 01:00:45.360
in community dating from 1619.

01:00:45.360 --> 01:00:49.490
Transported to the Chesapeake
region through Point Comfort,

01:00:49.490 --> 01:00:53.310
near present-day Hampton
and from thence to Jamestown

01:00:53.310 --> 01:00:57.300
and from there on to the
Weyanoke Plantation named

01:00:57.300 --> 01:01:01.100
for the indigenous
people who lived nearby,

01:01:01.100 --> 01:01:08.440
the 1619 Angolan Africans began
their lives in close proximity

01:01:08.440 --> 01:01:13.080
to an Algonquian-speaking
people whose ancestors had been

01:01:13.080 --> 01:01:19.630
in the region for at least
1,600 years before the English

01:01:19.630 --> 01:01:22.850
colonizers arrived.

01:01:22.850 --> 01:01:27.400
The Africans learned to hunt
and fish with the Weyanoke,

01:01:27.400 --> 01:01:29.990
lighting fires in
their canoes at night

01:01:29.990 --> 01:01:34.470
to warm their hands
and to attract fish.

01:01:34.470 --> 01:01:36.550
There were many similarities

01:01:36.550 --> 01:01:38.550
between the indigenous
read people

01:01:38.550 --> 01:01:41.750
and the transported Africans.

01:01:41.750 --> 01:01:46.050
Each was subjected to
"colonialism, social disorder

01:01:46.050 --> 01:01:48.000
and upheaval for
hundreds of years

01:01:48.000 --> 01:01:50.610
and to being called savages.

01:01:50.610 --> 01:01:54.250
The object of this immense and
intense culture interaction

01:01:54.250 --> 01:01:59.150
and it's resultant degradation
is the Weyanoke Association

01:01:59.150 --> 01:02:05.110
website points out, was
to take the red man's land

01:02:05.110 --> 01:02:10.250
and use the black man's
labor to work that land."

01:02:10.250 --> 01:02:15.260
On the positive side,

01:02:15.260 --> 01:02:20.160
the indigenous Native
American people

01:02:20.160 --> 01:02:24.150
and Africans alike had oral
traditions that allowed

01:02:24.150 --> 01:02:27.330
for the preservation of
ancestry and records.

01:02:27.330 --> 01:02:29.700
And the conveying of
identity and knowledge

01:02:29.700 --> 01:02:34.000
through the cultivation
of deep listening skill

01:02:34.000 --> 01:02:36.970
and respect for the elders.

01:02:36.970 --> 01:02:40.890
These were skills that
could spell the difference

01:02:40.890 --> 01:02:45.940
between physical
survival and annihilation.

01:02:45.940 --> 01:02:50.080
As folkways had the power to
give direction and guidance

01:02:50.080 --> 01:02:52.540
from ancestral knowledge,

01:02:52.540 --> 01:02:57.520
even when no ancestor
was physically present.

01:02:57.520 --> 01:03:00.930
And in many ways, the
Africans' spirituality

01:03:00.930 --> 01:03:04.920
and cosmology may have
been compatible with that

01:03:04.920 --> 01:03:07.890
of their original
indigenous hosts,

01:03:07.890 --> 01:03:10.890
along with their musical
traditions and practices

01:03:10.890 --> 01:03:14.500
of midwifery or biology
and other forms

01:03:14.500 --> 01:03:17.070
of traditional healing.

01:03:17.070 --> 01:03:20.720
Both peoples had
priests, conjurers,

01:03:20.720 --> 01:03:24.010
diviners and midwives.

01:03:24.010 --> 01:03:25.850
Each had a closeness

01:03:25.850 --> 01:03:32.790
and an interdependent
relationship to the land.

01:03:32.790 --> 01:03:35.870
By following the language
of the way that black

01:03:35.870 --> 01:03:40.390
and red people are described
in colonial Virginia laws,

01:03:40.390 --> 01:03:44.880
it is possible to see how
ideas of race changed over time

01:03:44.880 --> 01:03:49.550
and were used as tools
to divide two people

01:03:49.550 --> 01:03:52.180
who had much in common.

01:03:52.180 --> 01:03:58.010
As documented by Arica Coleman
in her award-winning book,

01:03:58.010 --> 01:04:01.310
That the Blood Stay
Pure, African-Americans,

01:04:01.310 --> 01:04:04.390
Native-Americans and the
predicament of identity

01:04:04.390 --> 01:04:09.410
in Virginia, relations between
indigenous persons and persons

01:04:09.410 --> 01:04:14.670
of African dissent in Virginia
have often been troubled

01:04:14.670 --> 01:04:19.330
with Virginia's Racial Purity
Act disrupting relationships

01:04:19.330 --> 01:04:25.180
among individuals,
families, churches and tribes.

01:04:25.180 --> 01:04:30.510
Today, the Weyanoke Association
founded by Hugh and Anita Herald

01:04:30.510 --> 01:04:37.860
in 1999 on the 380th anniversary
of the landing of Africans

01:04:37.860 --> 01:04:44.150
in Virginia has become a site
of memory and spiritual healing

01:04:44.150 --> 01:04:49.700
for those simultaneously
remembering, navigating

01:04:49.700 --> 01:04:55.940
and reconciling with this
rich and complicated past.

01:04:55.940 --> 01:05:01.580
When I speak of red-black
spirit medicine, I am speaking

01:05:01.580 --> 01:05:08.240
of medicine that originates with
red or black people that is good

01:05:08.240 --> 01:05:14.310
for black-red people, or anyone
else who needs the physical,

01:05:14.310 --> 01:05:17.170
emotional or psychological care

01:05:17.170 --> 01:05:21.790
that red-black spirit
medicine can provide.

01:05:21.790 --> 01:05:25.170
Think of it as complementary
care

01:05:25.170 --> 01:05:28.660
for the body, mind and spirit.

01:05:28.660 --> 01:05:34.600
Think of it as redress, to
use Saidiya Hartman's term,

01:05:34.600 --> 01:05:39.280
or soul repair for the
intersecting layers of violence

01:05:39.280 --> 01:05:45.020
and historical trauma and spirit
murder, to borrow from the work

01:05:45.020 --> 01:05:49.830
of Nell Painter and later
Kelly Brown Douglas.

01:05:49.830 --> 01:05:52.750
The work of Jack Saul has shown

01:05:52.750 --> 01:05:56.800
that collective trauma
is often best addressed

01:05:56.800 --> 01:05:59.810
in community with others.

01:05:59.810 --> 01:06:02.780
That is what the Weyanoke
Association achieves

01:06:02.780 --> 01:06:07.580
in their annual coming
together gatherings and powwows.

01:06:07.580 --> 01:06:12.460
The healing may attract
physical health, excuse me,

01:06:12.460 --> 01:06:16.840
may impact physical
health or just the spirit.

01:06:16.840 --> 01:06:20.810
I felt that healing personally

01:06:20.810 --> 01:06:25.960
when Hugh Harrell poured a
fresh pot of sassafras tea,

01:06:25.960 --> 01:06:31.010
and we sat down in a home rich
with art and ritual objects

01:06:31.010 --> 01:06:34.710
from both African and
indigenous culture.

01:06:34.710 --> 01:06:41.450
And Anita Harrell read
a poem called It isn't

01:06:41.450 --> 01:06:43.760
Identity Politics.

01:06:43.760 --> 01:06:48.650
Here's the poem.

01:06:49.990 --> 01:06:52.710
I am Anita Harrell.

01:06:52.710 --> 01:06:55.730
I am Moon Dancer.

01:06:55.730 --> 01:07:00.150
I am the daughter of Allene
[phonetic] Davis Alan.

01:07:00.150 --> 01:07:05.400
I am the daughter of
Annie Miles Davis Heron.

01:07:05.400 --> 01:07:09.560
I am the great-granddaughter
of N.E. [phonetic] Smith Miles.

01:07:09.560 --> 01:07:14.090
I am the great-great
granddaughter of Lavenia Smith.

01:07:14.090 --> 01:07:17.190
Because of them, I am Shoshone.

01:07:17.190 --> 01:07:20.030
Because of them, I am loved.

01:07:20.030 --> 01:07:23.010
Because of them, I am strong.

01:07:23.010 --> 01:07:28.530
Because of them, I
am who I say I am.

01:07:28.530 --> 01:07:30.680
I am Moon Dancer.

01:07:30.680 --> 01:07:33.360
I am Anita Harrel.

01:07:33.360 --> 01:07:34.660
Who are you?

01:07:34.660 --> 01:07:45.310
And then she said, if you
use a blood quantum approach,

01:07:45.310 --> 01:07:51.490
you are essentially
committing suicide, end quote.

01:07:51.490 --> 01:07:54.270
Hugh, a descendant
of many generations

01:07:54.270 --> 01:07:57.180
of Charles City County
red-blacks agrees.

01:07:57.180 --> 01:08:01.170
He says, we've been doing
what we've been doing

01:08:01.170 --> 01:08:03.180
because we had to.

01:08:03.180 --> 01:08:05.210
There's no emphasis
in local schools

01:08:05.210 --> 01:08:09.170
on teaching children
their history.

01:08:09.170 --> 01:08:14.600
Anita added, I know
Erica started her work,

01:08:14.600 --> 01:08:19.710
this is Dr. Arica Coleman, I
know Erica started her work

01:08:19.710 --> 01:08:22.920
after coming to one
of our gatherings.

01:08:22.920 --> 01:08:26.340
There's an alignment
with the ancestors.

01:08:26.340 --> 01:08:32.720
Things happening beyond
our control, end quote.

01:08:32.720 --> 01:08:35.520
Each year, on the second
Saturday in August,

01:08:35.520 --> 01:08:38.140
to coincide with the
anniversary of their arrival

01:08:38.140 --> 01:08:40.670
of the first Africans
in Virginia,

01:08:40.670 --> 01:08:43.700
the Weyanoke Association
sponsors the Coming Together

01:08:43.700 --> 01:08:49.850
Festival, the Lincoln legacy of
Native and African-Americans.

01:08:49.850 --> 01:08:51.610
To embark on a journey

01:08:51.610 --> 01:08:54.570
to a Weyanoke Coming
Together Festival,

01:08:54.570 --> 01:08:58.980
one must leave physically
the spaces and places

01:08:58.980 --> 01:09:04.030
of colonization and go into the
wilderness, up into the woods

01:09:04.030 --> 01:09:06.650
in Charles City County
or Surry County

01:09:06.650 --> 01:09:10.510
into historically
red and black spaces.

01:09:10.510 --> 01:09:14.410
One leaves Richmond, the
capital of the Confederacy

01:09:14.410 --> 01:09:17.410
or colonial Williamsburg,
literally

01:09:17.410 --> 01:09:20.940
and historically the
colonial capital.

01:09:20.940 --> 01:09:23.810
From Williamsburg,
one drives west

01:09:23.810 --> 01:09:27.680
on Route 5 past Weyanoke
Plantation

01:09:27.680 --> 01:09:32.030
where Yardley hid most of
the 19 Angolan Africans

01:09:32.030 --> 01:09:36.390
who were imported illegally
into Jamestown in 1619.

01:09:36.390 --> 01:09:39.070
And then on past
Berkley Plantation

01:09:39.070 --> 01:09:42.660
where Benjamin Harrison
traded extensively

01:09:42.660 --> 01:09:45.060
with indigenous people.

01:09:45.060 --> 01:09:48.170
And some Weyanoke
people lived in houses

01:09:48.170 --> 01:09:51.730
on that Harrison property.

01:09:51.730 --> 01:09:57.440
There, on the Weyanoke
Peninsula, just five miles

01:09:57.440 --> 01:10:01.430
from the place where the
indentured Africans formed their

01:10:01.430 --> 01:10:04.160
first community.

01:10:04.160 --> 01:10:08.450
In fact, many of the Coming
Together gatherings have been

01:10:08.450 --> 01:10:12.860
held as the Harrison
National Fish Hatcheries,

01:10:12.860 --> 01:10:15.870
part of the original
Harrison Estate,

01:10:15.870 --> 01:10:20.630
which keeps the historical
continuities tight.

01:10:20.630 --> 01:10:24.840
To go to Coming Together, one
travels through greenspaces

01:10:24.840 --> 01:10:28.600
and through symbolic geography
and psychic landscapes

01:10:28.600 --> 01:10:32.980
to become removed,
sheltered and inoculated.

01:10:32.980 --> 01:10:36.260
To claim and be reclaimed.

01:10:36.260 --> 01:10:41.510
Once arrived, the healing can
begin in ways large and small

01:10:41.510 --> 01:10:45.990
in spaces where the mind
can begin to be decolonized,

01:10:45.990 --> 01:10:49.340
and everyone is invited
to break bread

01:10:49.340 --> 01:10:53.310
and enjoy the transcendent
rhythms of sacred drums,

01:10:53.310 --> 01:10:55.780
healing songs and chants,

01:10:55.780 --> 01:11:00.130
processions honoring the
ancestors and dancing.

01:11:00.130 --> 01:11:05.350
The protocol of Coming
Together includes both African

01:11:05.350 --> 01:11:08.170
and Native elements.

01:11:08.170 --> 01:11:10.250
Everyone is welcome.

01:11:10.250 --> 01:11:15.650
But one must be intentional
about the choice

01:11:15.650 --> 01:11:19.580
to make the journey to go there.

01:11:19.580 --> 01:11:21.760
Walking in a Weyanoke procession

01:11:21.760 --> 01:11:23.820
and hearing the transcendent
rhythms

01:11:23.820 --> 01:11:27.700
of two cultures can
be a powerful source

01:11:27.700 --> 01:11:29.960
of reconnection and renewal.

01:11:29.960 --> 01:11:35.720
Especially for one who
has read in black roots.

01:11:35.720 --> 01:11:38.110
There is medicine in
the knowledge shared,

01:11:38.110 --> 01:11:42.560
in the smudging, in the
libations, in the prayers,

01:11:42.560 --> 01:11:45.830
in the food, in the belonging.

01:11:45.830 --> 01:11:48.510
For me, the Who's Afraid

01:11:48.510 --> 01:11:59.100
of Black Indians poems,
talk about a slip.

01:11:59.100 --> 01:12:04.230
For me, the Who's Afraid
of Black Indians poems

01:12:04.230 --> 01:12:11.900
of Weyanoke Association member
Shonda Buchanan are restorative.

01:12:11.900 --> 01:12:14.750
Not unlike the narrative
medicine I've taught

01:12:14.750 --> 01:12:19.450
at William &amp; Mary and Eastern
Virginia Medical School,

01:12:19.450 --> 01:12:22.410
there is more medicine
in the photographs

01:12:22.410 --> 01:12:28.110
of Faith Charity Nelson
and Valena Dismukes

01:12:28.110 --> 01:12:30.810
and in the paintings
of Rose Paliton

01:12:30.810 --> 01:12:35.530
and the pottery of
Lynnette Allston.

01:12:35.530 --> 01:12:40.120
Beyond this, Anita Harrell
has taken her healing rituals

01:12:40.120 --> 01:12:45.200
into her work as a family
system's constellations therapy

01:12:45.200 --> 01:12:50.360
facilitator, and similar
therapies were recently employed

01:12:50.360 --> 01:12:56.440
in a Braxton Institute advanced
training seminar for 100 helpers

01:12:56.440 --> 01:13:00.670
and healers seeking
training in moral injury

01:13:00.670 --> 01:13:06.140
and collective healing
in September 2017.

01:13:06.140 --> 01:13:07.440
African-American

01:13:07.440 --> 01:13:13.830
and Native-American healers have
access to knowledge, culture

01:13:13.830 --> 01:13:19.860
and power when we stand in our
own medicine and our own truth.

01:13:19.860 --> 01:13:24.090
I conclude with a prayer

01:13:24.090 --> 01:13:27.930
from the Weyanoke
Association website.

01:13:29.740 --> 01:13:35.570
We give thanks to the
Creator for each new day.

01:13:35.570 --> 01:13:41.030
We give thanks to the
ancestors who watch over us.

01:13:41.030 --> 01:13:47.390
We give thanks to our Mother
Earth who sustains us.

01:13:47.390 --> 01:13:51.740
We give thanks to our brothers
and sisters, the plants

01:13:51.740 --> 01:13:57.910
and animals, who give our lives
so that ours may continue.

01:13:57.910 --> 01:14:01.880
We give thanks to the
people who've work,

01:14:01.880 --> 01:14:05.190
care and love nourish us.

01:14:05.190 --> 01:14:11.680
We give thanks that [inaudible]
and Turtle Island meet in us.

01:14:11.680 --> 01:14:16.270
We give thanks to the Creator
for all of these gifts.

01:14:16.270 --> 01:14:20.940
May they be transformed into
positive thoughts, careful

01:14:20.940 --> 01:14:28.190
and kind words, appropriate
and effective deeds.

01:14:28.190 --> 01:14:32.470
Aho [phonetic], [Foreign
Language] Amen.

01:14:32.470 --> 01:14:34.150
&gt;&gt; Aho.

01:14:34.150 --> 01:14:37.210
&gt;&gt; Joanne M. Braxton: Aho.

01:14:37.210 --> 01:14:39.510
Thank you.

01:14:39.510 --> 01:14:51.520
[ Applause ]

01:14:51.520 --> 01:14:55.970
I'm going to shift now to
our panel discussion mode.

01:15:05.090 --> 01:15:08.060
There's no graceful way
to pick up index cards.

01:15:10.690 --> 01:15:20.280
Before we get started, I would
like to acknowledge the presence

01:15:20.280 --> 01:15:25.130
of Nancy Rodriguez and
Uri [phonetic] Mulligan

01:15:25.130 --> 01:15:31.210
from Commemoration 2918,
American Evolution.

01:15:31.210 --> 01:15:33.010
Would you please stand up?

01:15:33.010 --> 01:15:38.240
[ Applause ]

01:15:38.240 --> 01:15:42.250
Thank you for your
support of this program.

01:15:42.250 --> 01:15:45.340
Dr. Newby-Alexander,
we began working

01:15:45.340 --> 01:15:48.540
on our collaborative 2019
commemoration efforts

01:15:48.540 --> 01:15:52.730
in preparation for the 400th
anniversary of 1619 way back

01:15:52.730 --> 01:16:00.770
in 2012 when we collectively
convened the first 1619

01:16:00.770 --> 01:16:04.540
and Making of America conference
at Norfolk State University.

01:16:04.540 --> 01:16:08.750
Since that time, we have
constituted ourselves

01:16:08.750 --> 01:16:11.320
as a learning community,
a kind of think tank

01:16:11.320 --> 01:16:15.050
for revisiting the discussion
of 1619 and its impact

01:16:15.050 --> 01:16:19.000
and significance in
American history.

01:16:19.000 --> 01:16:22.960
So our team has been
working on this for years.

01:16:22.960 --> 01:16:25.450
Why?

01:16:25.450 --> 01:16:27.010
&gt;&gt; Cassandra Newby-Alexander:
You know,

01:16:27.010 --> 01:16:29.320
it is a difficult story.

01:16:29.320 --> 01:16:32.450
What we have to do is
deconstruct the way

01:16:32.450 --> 01:16:36.560
in which we see our
nation's history.

01:16:36.560 --> 01:16:39.880
The center of the
story has focused

01:16:39.880 --> 01:16:43.190
on the European descendants.

01:16:43.190 --> 01:16:49.740
And everyone else has been
left out or completely ignored.

01:16:49.740 --> 01:16:53.760
And so we brought together
not only scholars but people

01:16:53.760 --> 01:16:58.210
in the community to
tell a different story.

01:16:58.210 --> 01:17:01.880
To tell a story that's
really who we are.

01:17:01.880 --> 01:17:06.420
And we started with asking the
question, who are we really?

01:17:06.420 --> 01:17:09.330
And all you have to do
is peel back the layers

01:17:09.330 --> 01:17:13.520
of your own family's
history and legacy to know

01:17:13.520 --> 01:17:17.810
that the story you tell your
children is not the real story.

01:17:17.810 --> 01:17:19.500
You tell the good.

01:17:19.500 --> 01:17:23.410
You tell the part of that
story that makes you proud,

01:17:23.410 --> 01:17:27.030
that makes you feel
like you have ownership.

01:17:27.030 --> 01:17:29.660
But our story is
much more complex.

01:17:29.660 --> 01:17:32.700
And so in retelling a story,

01:17:32.700 --> 01:17:35.410
in pulling all the
different layers out,

01:17:35.410 --> 01:17:37.420
the need to be removed,

01:17:37.420 --> 01:17:41.790
and putting into that
narrative what really needs

01:17:41.790 --> 01:17:44.260
to be there, it takes a while.

01:17:44.260 --> 01:17:48.050
And as you can see even
in today's politics,

01:17:48.050 --> 01:17:50.680
people are afraid of that story.

01:17:50.680 --> 01:17:53.570
But that's the story
that makes us strong.

01:17:53.570 --> 01:17:56.410
That's the story
that makes us unique.

01:17:56.410 --> 01:18:01.550
That should be the story
that makes us proud.

01:18:01.550 --> 01:18:02.850
&gt;&gt; Joanne M. Braxton: Thank you.

01:18:02.850 --> 01:18:10.970
In connection with the original
2012 1619 and the Making

01:18:10.970 --> 01:18:14.690
of America conference
at Norfolk State,

01:18:14.690 --> 01:18:19.390
I interviewed Dr. Maya Angelou,
and I'd like to bring her

01:18:19.390 --> 01:18:24.930
into the room with us right now.

01:18:29.520 --> 01:18:36.640
I asked why should 1619 be on
our minds as we face forward

01:18:36.640 --> 01:18:40.030
into the 400th anniversary
of the arrival of Africans

01:18:40.030 --> 01:18:42.930
and women in the English
colony of Virginia?

01:18:42.930 --> 01:18:46.700
What are the enduring
questions raised

01:18:46.700 --> 01:18:49.250
by this pivotal moment in time?

01:18:49.250 --> 01:18:56.440
And now, I'm quoting Dr.
Maya Angelou who said,

01:18:56.440 --> 01:19:02.500
"We have an old saying that has
become a cliché and that is,

01:19:02.500 --> 01:19:04.630
you can't know where
you're going unless you know

01:19:04.630 --> 01:19:06.900
where you've been.

01:19:06.900 --> 01:19:09.450
It is imperative," she said,

01:19:09.450 --> 01:19:12.490
"that all Americans
recognize the imprint

01:19:12.490 --> 01:19:14.320
of the first Africans
brought here

01:19:14.320 --> 01:19:18.400
and the first white women
brought here in bondage.

01:19:18.400 --> 01:19:20.770
I'm trying to say
that the word slavery

01:19:20.770 --> 01:19:26.270
and the term enslavement has
lost so much of its weight,

01:19:26.270 --> 01:19:28.050
until the people mouth the words

01:19:28.050 --> 01:19:33.030
without realizing what they're
saying, what they're calling up.

01:19:33.030 --> 01:19:37.540
When you read the history of
the enslavement, the hundreds

01:19:37.540 --> 01:19:40.720
of years of enslavement,
it's too dreadful

01:19:40.720 --> 01:19:42.380
to have even been included

01:19:42.380 --> 01:19:44.930
in Alex Haley's phenomena
the book Roots

01:19:44.930 --> 01:19:49.440
and the television phenomena
Roots in which I," Maya Angelou

01:19:49.440 --> 01:19:53.370
"played Kunta Kinte's
grandmother.

01:19:53.370 --> 01:19:55.140
Too bizarre.

01:19:55.140 --> 01:19:57.840
Too horrible," she says.

01:19:57.840 --> 01:20:03.230
"And yet, we have to face
it or we will never get rid

01:20:03.230 --> 01:20:07.740
of this blight of racism and
guilt and hate which assembles

01:20:07.740 --> 01:20:11.090
in our race in the
21st century."

01:20:11.090 --> 01:20:19.320
Panelists, do you
agree with Dr. Angelou?

01:20:19.320 --> 01:20:21.980
Why or why not?

01:20:21.980 --> 01:20:25.830
What do you feel are the
enduring questions raised

01:20:25.830 --> 01:20:32.160
by 1619 for those of
us still here in 2018?

01:20:32.160 --> 01:20:36.970
Is 2019 another pivotal moment?

01:20:36.970 --> 01:20:44.000
How can having access to the
past, and in particular, 1619,

01:20:44.000 --> 01:20:46.970
help us understand the present?

01:20:51.120 --> 01:20:53.030
&gt;&gt; Who first?

01:20:53.030 --> 01:20:54.330
&gt;&gt; Joanne M. Braxton:
Dr. Vinson.

01:20:54.330 --> 01:20:55.630
&gt;&gt; Robert Trent Vinson:
I'll take a stab at that.

01:20:55.630 --> 01:20:56.930
Let's see.

01:20:56.930 --> 01:21:00.570
So, 2019 is the 400th
anniversary of 1619,

01:21:00.570 --> 01:21:02.240
which we're talking about.

01:21:02.240 --> 01:21:06.000
And so it gives a chance to talk
about Jamestown and to put it

01:21:06.000 --> 01:21:09.250
into context in terms
of the world.

01:21:09.250 --> 01:21:13.110
Because on some level,
Jamestown and the context

01:21:13.110 --> 01:21:16.710
of the Atlantic slave
trade was peripheral.

01:21:16.710 --> 01:21:19.540
I already mentioned 500,000
Africans had already come

01:21:19.540 --> 01:21:21.410
across the water.

01:21:21.410 --> 01:21:25.450
Only 6% of Africans coming
across the water actually came

01:21:25.450 --> 01:21:27.520
to what became the
United States.

01:21:27.520 --> 01:21:30.370
The vast majority, over
90%, went to South America,

01:21:30.370 --> 01:21:33.150
Central America and
the Caribbean.

01:21:33.150 --> 01:21:40.070
Yet, what developed starting
from Jamestown was ultimately

01:21:40.070 --> 01:21:43.520
by 1860, the largest slave
society in world history,

01:21:43.520 --> 01:21:47.300
four million enslaved
people, right.

01:21:47.300 --> 01:21:51.860
And we have to deal with
that dynamic of how it was

01:21:51.860 --> 01:21:54.870
that a system of slavery that
has been a global phenomena,

01:21:54.870 --> 01:21:58.590
it's in all the ancient
societies,

01:21:58.590 --> 01:22:01.000
became so heavily race-based.

01:22:01.000 --> 01:22:05.330
And the system of slavery which
has a classic component, right,

01:22:05.330 --> 01:22:08.960
appropriating labor to generate
profit for someone else,

01:22:08.960 --> 01:22:12.720
included a racial component
now to create this kind

01:22:12.720 --> 01:22:18.650
of racial caste system that
in many ways survived slavery

01:22:18.650 --> 01:22:20.150
in a legal sense.

01:22:20.150 --> 01:22:25.320
And so Jamestown gives
us a chance to reflect

01:22:25.320 --> 01:22:31.240
and shift the narrative, because
if we look at 1619 and we go

01:22:31.240 --> 01:22:36.540
to 1865, that's 246 years of
slavery, which is more years

01:22:36.540 --> 01:22:39.300
than of freedom in this country.

01:22:39.300 --> 01:22:42.060
And then if you look at
those years of freedom,

01:22:42.060 --> 01:22:46.840
the great majority of that time,
over 100 years, is Jim Crow.

01:22:46.840 --> 01:22:51.300
So when we talk about
Jamestown being the beginning

01:22:51.300 --> 01:22:53.850
of democracy, that's
from the perspective

01:22:53.850 --> 01:22:56.790
of propertied white men.

01:22:56.790 --> 01:23:01.300
Democracy is a rather new
thing in America I would argue.

01:23:01.300 --> 01:23:03.410
I would argue that we might
have to start thinking

01:23:03.410 --> 01:23:08.850
about democracy perhaps with
the Voting Rights Act of 1965.

01:23:08.850 --> 01:23:15.220
And even then, it's a fragile
thing as we've come to know.

01:23:16.330 --> 01:23:19.620
So we have the largest
prison population

01:23:19.620 --> 01:23:21.460
in world history as well.

01:23:21.460 --> 01:23:24.120
And we know those who
are branded as felons,

01:23:24.120 --> 01:23:26.490
even after they've served
their time and paid their debt

01:23:26.490 --> 01:23:31.130
to society, still very difficult
to get their voting rights back

01:23:31.130 --> 01:23:32.430
and other rights as well.

01:23:32.430 --> 01:23:38.920
So 2019 gives us a moment
to reflect on where we are

01:23:38.920 --> 01:23:42.860
in America and where
America is in the world.

01:23:42.860 --> 01:23:47.380
That's the best I can do
with such a deep question.

01:23:47.380 --> 01:23:49.510
&gt;&gt; That's the best you can do?

01:23:49.510 --> 01:23:56.080
[ Applause ]

01:23:56.080 --> 01:23:57.890
&gt;&gt; Lynnette Lewis Allston: Well,
I want to chime in on that,

01:23:57.890 --> 01:23:59.860
because in Native America,

01:23:59.860 --> 01:24:04.060
we deal with what we
call historical trauma.

01:24:04.060 --> 01:24:08.960
And it's the mindset, the things
that we have carried with us

01:24:08.960 --> 01:24:13.680
through the generations
that control how we interact

01:24:13.680 --> 01:24:19.610
with people, what we say,
what we are afraid to say.

01:24:19.610 --> 01:24:24.340
Because we feel we, we're
the lowest of the low.

01:24:24.340 --> 01:24:30.140
That was what 1619,
1607 began to do

01:24:30.140 --> 01:24:36.410
to our culture was make
us afraid of who we are.

01:24:36.410 --> 01:24:38.930
So that historical trauma
is still something we're

01:24:38.930 --> 01:24:40.230
dealing with.

01:24:40.230 --> 01:24:41.590
We are just beginning to talk

01:24:41.590 --> 01:24:45.360
about our history,
our perspective.

01:24:45.360 --> 01:24:49.230
And it is a revelation.

01:24:49.230 --> 01:24:57.790
It is an opportunity to release,
and we look forward to the 2019

01:24:57.790 --> 01:25:01.770
to let us have a voice
at the table to talk more

01:25:01.770 --> 01:25:04.440
about our perspective.

01:25:06.510 --> 01:25:11.600
[ Applause ]

01:25:11.600 --> 01:25:13.520
&gt;&gt; Cassandra Newby-Alexander:
So I will chime in as well.

01:25:13.520 --> 01:25:19.270
One of the things that I,
I'm going to compare this to,

01:25:19.270 --> 01:25:22.970
if you visit a plantation
anywhere in the South

01:25:22.970 --> 01:25:28.520
in America, you hear the
story of a handful of people

01:25:28.520 --> 01:25:33.140
who own the plantation,
their lives, their traumas,

01:25:33.140 --> 01:25:36.430
what they ate, what they
wore, whether they died,

01:25:36.430 --> 01:25:38.590
whether they had diseases.

01:25:38.590 --> 01:25:44.190
But you don't hear anything
about people who made sure

01:25:44.190 --> 01:25:50.550
that that plantation thrived,
survived, produced the goods.

01:25:50.550 --> 01:25:55.560
You don't hear about the trauma
that those individuals endured.

01:25:55.560 --> 01:25:58.780
You don't hear about
the work that went

01:25:58.780 --> 01:26:03.760
into creating this
plantation that thrived.

01:26:03.760 --> 01:26:07.260
You don't read about how
these were the individuals

01:26:07.260 --> 01:26:11.640
who actually built, or
constructed the buildings,

01:26:11.640 --> 01:26:17.280
planted the fields, maintained
the economic integrity

01:26:17.280 --> 01:26:19.890
of that particular plantation.

01:26:19.890 --> 01:26:23.770
For you, the visitor,
they are invisible.

01:26:23.770 --> 01:26:30.090
They are the side story that you
don't even really get to hear.

01:26:30.090 --> 01:26:35.350
And so going back
400 years is critical

01:26:35.350 --> 01:26:37.850
to the survival of our country.

01:26:37.850 --> 01:26:43.270
Because we have created such a
false narrative of who we are.

01:26:43.270 --> 01:26:46.940
We've created, sustained
and held

01:26:46.940 --> 01:26:53.530
on with both hands
this lie about America.

01:26:53.530 --> 01:26:57.700
This lie about how the
English arrived and bam,

01:26:57.700 --> 01:27:03.170
there was this gorgeous
creative, incredible nation

01:27:03.170 --> 01:27:06.270
that sprang out of nothing.

01:27:06.270 --> 01:27:09.980
With no one else's help
but the handful of English

01:27:09.980 --> 01:27:13.730
who first arrived and
their descendants.

01:27:13.730 --> 01:27:15.730
That's the narrative
that you hear.

01:27:15.730 --> 01:27:17.690
But that is a lie.

01:27:17.690 --> 01:27:23.580
And so it is critical that we
go back and not only deconstruct

01:27:23.580 --> 01:27:29.190
that lie but tell you why the
truth is far more important

01:27:29.190 --> 01:27:34.880
and far more of a guide to
who we can be for the future.

01:27:34.880 --> 01:27:41.270
And so, you know, in history,
sometimes it takes distance

01:27:41.270 --> 01:27:45.340
from a certain event
for us to really begin

01:27:45.340 --> 01:27:48.760
to want to face our pain.

01:27:48.760 --> 01:27:51.720
And today, in today's
society, you have a number

01:27:51.720 --> 01:27:53.890
of psychologists
and sociologists

01:27:53.890 --> 01:27:59.450
who are now studying this
posttraumatic stress disorder

01:27:59.450 --> 01:28:01.530
that many people of African

01:28:01.530 --> 01:28:04.740
and Native descent
have been experiencing

01:28:04.740 --> 01:28:10.010
for the past 400 plus
years in this society.

01:28:10.010 --> 01:28:11.930
Many people talk about, well,

01:28:11.930 --> 01:28:14.250
why aren't African-Americans
thriving

01:28:14.250 --> 01:28:17.430
like all these other immigrants
coming to this country?

01:28:17.430 --> 01:28:19.830
Well, none of the other
immigrants have to go

01:28:19.830 --> 01:28:24.220
through an ongoing process that
African-Americans went through.

01:28:24.220 --> 01:28:28.400
So it comforts us
to blame the victim

01:28:28.400 --> 01:28:30.270
for their own victimization

01:28:30.270 --> 01:28:34.120
and to ignore the
realities of our society.

01:28:34.120 --> 01:28:37.980
We talk about the
poverty and the alcoholism

01:28:37.980 --> 01:28:41.620
of the Native peoples, but we
don't talk about how we put many

01:28:41.620 --> 01:28:46.430
of them on land that not even
a tumbleweed survives on.

01:28:46.430 --> 01:28:49.760
And so we, this is the time.

01:28:49.760 --> 01:28:56.090
This is the time when America
can look back and begin

01:28:56.090 --> 01:29:01.510
to reconcile itself
with its own truth.

01:29:01.510 --> 01:29:08.340
