01:45:45.470 --> 01:45:46.770
&gt;&gt; Robert Trent Vinson: Yes.

01:45:46.770 --> 01:45:48.070
&gt;&gt; Yes indeed.

01:45:48.070 --> 01:45:49.500
[ Applause ]

01:45:49.500 --> 01:45:50.800
Yes indeed.

01:45:50.800 --> 01:45:52.100
Very happy, because she's coming

01:45:52.100 --> 01:45:53.400
from my alma mater,
Smith College.

01:45:53.400 --> 01:45:54.700
So I'm very happy about that.

01:45:54.700 --> 01:45:57.110
I wanted to address my
question to you though.

01:45:57.110 --> 01:46:00.050
I was really struck, this is
a statistic I had never heard

01:46:00.050 --> 01:46:05.620
before about the low percentage
of the African enslaved people

01:46:05.620 --> 01:46:08.200
who were taken to
Jamestown or North America

01:46:08.200 --> 01:46:09.500
as opposed to South America.

01:46:09.500 --> 01:46:11.740
And then you mention, of course,

01:46:11.740 --> 01:46:15.700
that this American South became
the largest slaveholding society

01:46:15.700 --> 01:46:17.000
in the world.

01:46:17.000 --> 01:46:19.270
Can you, this is a very, a
question that you could write

01:46:19.270 --> 01:46:23.430
and probably have written
thousands of books on, but why,

01:46:23.430 --> 01:46:27.170
what conditions made
North America the place

01:46:27.170 --> 01:46:29.210
for the largest slaveholding
society

01:46:29.210 --> 01:46:31.660
as opposed to South America?

01:46:31.660 --> 01:46:33.170
&gt;&gt; Robert Trent Vinson: Right.

01:46:33.170 --> 01:46:34.770
That's a big broad question

01:46:34.770 --> 01:46:38.470
that I can give you the short
answer is that slaveholders

01:46:38.470 --> 01:46:41.210
in South America,
Central America

01:46:41.210 --> 01:46:43.780
and the Caribbean
basically made a calculus

01:46:43.780 --> 01:46:45.200
that it was cheaper simply

01:46:45.200 --> 01:46:48.540
to keep importing
enslaved Africans.

01:46:48.540 --> 01:46:50.230
And so literally, you know,

01:46:50.230 --> 01:46:51.750
folk coming into the
Caribbean [inaudible]

01:46:51.750 --> 01:46:53.900
since the average lifespan
after arriving in the Caribbean,

01:46:53.900 --> 01:46:56.180
and these are people
in their prime,

01:46:56.180 --> 01:46:57.950
their high teens, early 20s.

01:46:57.950 --> 01:47:01.290
The average lifespan of
survival was seven years.

01:47:01.290 --> 01:47:05.320
And we're talking about
a population that's

01:47:05.320 --> 01:47:07.350
about two-thirds male.

01:47:07.350 --> 01:47:10.140
So those two dynamics are
simply, it's cheaper just

01:47:10.140 --> 01:47:11.920
to work them to death, work them
to death, work them to death,

01:47:11.920 --> 01:47:14.320
and we'll just import
more, right.

01:47:14.320 --> 01:47:17.030
And the gender imbalance meant
that there was a constant,

01:47:17.030 --> 01:47:20.020
constant influx of
more people coming in.

01:47:20.020 --> 01:47:22.810
So that was why the
numbers were so much higher.

01:47:22.810 --> 01:47:26.300
So that was the center of the
gravity for the slave trade.

01:47:26.300 --> 01:47:31.760
By contrast, North America was
really a type of backwater.

01:47:31.760 --> 01:47:36.100
And so the way that Angela
and her fellow captors made it

01:47:36.100 --> 01:47:39.120
to Jamestown was really an
accident of history, right.

01:47:39.120 --> 01:47:43.770
They were on their way to the
epicenter, in this case, Mexico.

01:47:43.770 --> 01:47:47.300
And because of those two ships,
they were rerouted, right.

01:47:47.300 --> 01:47:50.470
And so ultimately, and then
the United States banned the

01:47:50.470 --> 01:47:53.840
importation of enslaved
people in 1807,

01:47:53.840 --> 01:47:55.800
even though there was some
illegal activity going

01:47:55.800 --> 01:47:58.950
on as late as 1859,
short footnote.

01:47:58.950 --> 01:48:04.610
But the dynamic there was
natural reproduction became the

01:48:04.610 --> 01:48:06.220
preferred method if
you would, right.

01:48:06.220 --> 01:48:09.970
And so in that time, we
have tremendous growth.

01:48:09.970 --> 01:48:12.170
Right. In this way
too, we have to look

01:48:12.170 --> 01:48:16.550
at the Louisiana Purchase as
an important event as well.

01:48:16.550 --> 01:48:19.890
That doesn't happen without
the Haitian Revolution, right.

01:48:19.890 --> 01:48:21.490
That's the first thing to say.

01:48:21.490 --> 01:48:24.160
When Napoleon loses
Santa Mon [phonetic],

01:48:24.160 --> 01:48:26.770
the largest slave-producing
island for them.

01:48:26.770 --> 01:48:28.350
That becomes Haiti.

01:48:28.350 --> 01:48:32.760
Essentially, he has less of a
need for French North America.

01:48:32.760 --> 01:48:35.100
And he's trying to
finance his wars in Europe.

01:48:35.100 --> 01:48:41.590
And so he sells what becomes
the Midwest United States

01:48:41.590 --> 01:48:44.100
from Louisiana to
Canada for $15 million

01:48:44.100 --> 01:48:45.550
in the Louisiana Purchase.

01:48:45.550 --> 01:48:48.950
So Jefferson declares this as
an empire for liberty, right,

01:48:48.950 --> 01:48:50.850
double the size of
the United States.

01:48:50.850 --> 01:48:53.010
It really becomes an
empire for slavery

01:48:53.010 --> 01:48:55.160
because there's a second
middle passage that happens

01:48:55.160 --> 01:48:58.430
where a million people and
slave people move from states

01:48:58.430 --> 01:49:02.810
like Virginia to places like
Louisiana, Mississippi, Alabama.

01:49:02.810 --> 01:49:04.110
So doubling the size

01:49:04.110 --> 01:49:06.450
of the United States also
doubled the size of slavery.

01:49:06.450 --> 01:49:09.700
And so we had more
territory now, right.

01:49:09.700 --> 01:49:13.130
So that is why we get the US
South becoming the large slave

01:49:13.130 --> 01:49:14.430
society in world history.

01:49:14.430 --> 01:49:16.730
Okay? You're welcome.

01:49:22.290 --> 01:49:23.920
&gt;&gt; Thank you.

01:49:23.920 --> 01:49:29.680
Hello. I'm very interested in
what you all have had to say

01:49:29.680 --> 01:49:35.000
about collective trauma
in history and the need

01:49:35.000 --> 01:49:36.590
to dispel false narratives.

01:49:36.590 --> 01:49:38.770
And I was wondering what
any of you might have to say

01:49:38.770 --> 01:49:42.040
about the possibility of
reparations playing a role

01:49:42.040 --> 01:49:45.060
in that, not just
for African-Americans

01:49:45.060 --> 01:49:48.610
but also potentially Native
Americans with removal

01:49:48.610 --> 01:49:51.060
and if you feel that
could play a role,

01:49:51.060 --> 01:49:54.480
how such a conversation
could even be begun.

01:49:54.480 --> 01:50:01.860
&gt;&gt; Cassandra Newby-Alexander:
I'll take a stab at that one.

01:50:01.860 --> 01:50:04.870
What is interesting to me is
whenever you hear the term

01:50:04.870 --> 01:50:09.960
reparations, reparations
for formerly enslaved people

01:50:09.960 --> 01:50:13.030
and their descendants,
the nation seems

01:50:13.030 --> 01:50:19.400
to collectively just go
into trauma themselves.

01:50:19.400 --> 01:50:24.690
America has a real problem
with acknowledging its role,

01:50:24.690 --> 01:50:31.110
its guilt in sustaining even
our Constitution, sustaining

01:50:31.110 --> 01:50:34.130
and perpetuating and
protecting slavery.

01:50:34.130 --> 01:50:35.880
Most people are not taught

01:50:35.880 --> 01:50:40.290
that the original
Constitution protected one piece

01:50:40.290 --> 01:50:43.220
of property, enslaved people.

01:50:43.220 --> 01:50:49.240
For the rights of those
who were the slaveholders.

01:50:49.240 --> 01:50:53.910
Because the Fugitive Slave Act,
the three-fifths compromise,

01:50:53.910 --> 01:50:55.310
all of these things that were

01:50:55.310 --> 01:50:59.720
in the original Constitution
gave federal protection

01:50:59.720 --> 01:51:01.400
to slavery.

01:51:01.400 --> 01:51:06.670
And Virginia, of course,
was the largest state

01:51:06.670 --> 01:51:10.290
that had the largest
population of enslave people.

01:51:10.290 --> 01:51:12.020
In fact, for a long time,

01:51:12.020 --> 01:51:14.360
Virginia had the
largest population.

01:51:14.360 --> 01:51:19.600
That's kind of a duh, right,
because it was the first colony.

01:51:19.600 --> 01:51:22.790
And all these people
that Dr. Vinson talked

01:51:22.790 --> 01:51:27.520
about being transported to the
lower South, most of them were

01:51:27.520 --> 01:51:30.760
from Virginia, and
yet, as thousands

01:51:30.760 --> 01:51:34.310
of people were transported
beginning in the early 1900s

01:51:34.310 --> 01:51:37.950
to the lower South, the
population in Virginia

01:51:37.950 --> 01:51:39.350
of Africans

01:51:39.350 --> 01:51:42.260
and African-Americans
sustained itself.

01:51:42.260 --> 01:51:45.230
The reproduction was high
because of the kinds of crops

01:51:45.230 --> 01:51:47.880
that were being produced,
the kinds of industries,

01:51:47.880 --> 01:51:53.330
so much so that the
primary industry in Virginia

01:51:53.330 --> 01:51:58.350
by the 1820s and 30s was
the domestic slave trade.

01:51:58.350 --> 01:52:02.200
That is what Virginia made
most of this money from.

01:52:02.200 --> 01:52:08.570
And so everything went into
creating more enslaved people

01:52:08.570 --> 01:52:12.020
and making sure that
they survived to be part

01:52:12.020 --> 01:52:14.970
of this domestic slave trade.

01:52:14.970 --> 01:52:17.410
And so when we talk
about reparations,

01:52:17.410 --> 01:52:21.630
a lot of people focus in on
what happened to enslaved people

01:52:21.630 --> 01:52:24.340
and how their labor was
used for a long time.

01:52:24.340 --> 01:52:29.980
But I actually argue that
reparations really should be

01:52:29.980 --> 01:52:34.080
after 1865, after
the 13th Amendment,

01:52:34.080 --> 01:52:40.170
after the 14th Amendment when
African-Americans whose rights

01:52:40.170 --> 01:52:43.630
as human beings was now
federally recognized

01:52:43.630 --> 01:52:46.940
that the states and
federal government continued

01:52:46.940 --> 01:52:52.250
to deprive them of their
property, of their civil rights.

01:52:52.250 --> 01:52:54.990
They began to redline them.

01:52:54.990 --> 01:52:59.410
They began to make them pay
more money than white Americans

01:52:59.410 --> 01:53:02.170
for their property,
for their schools,

01:53:02.170 --> 01:53:06.050
even though their schools were
supposed to be equally funded,

01:53:06.050 --> 01:53:08.290
or at least funded
by property taxes.

01:53:08.290 --> 01:53:09.590
They weren't.

01:53:09.590 --> 01:53:13.180
In the 1940s, the
Journal and Guide,

01:53:13.180 --> 01:53:16.420
which was a black-owned
newspaper operating

01:53:16.420 --> 01:53:20.760
out of Norfolk, Virginia,
published an expose showing

01:53:20.760 --> 01:53:25.220
that Virginia systematically
took between 2

01:53:25.220 --> 01:53:31.490
and $30,000 a year from all
of the counties and cities

01:53:31.490 --> 01:53:34.050
in which African-Americans
were located.

01:53:34.050 --> 01:53:37.980
This is money that
African-Americans were paying

01:53:37.980 --> 01:53:42.130
in taxes to go to their schools,
and they were redirecting

01:53:42.130 --> 01:53:45.610
that money to the white schools.

01:53:45.610 --> 01:53:51.690
So we're not even talking about
paying somebody for labor.

01:53:51.690 --> 01:53:56.370
We're talking about real
dollars that were supposed to go

01:53:56.370 --> 01:53:59.780
to one thing, and they
were put to something else.

01:53:59.780 --> 01:54:02.990
So reparations is
an important way

01:54:02.990 --> 01:54:09.100
to start reinfusing our
communities and our society

01:54:09.100 --> 01:54:11.840
with money that should be there,

01:54:11.840 --> 01:54:13.830
should have been there
from the beginning.

01:54:13.830 --> 01:54:17.800
I'm at Norfolk State University,
a historically black college,

01:54:17.800 --> 01:54:20.820
or what they call black
college and university.

01:54:20.820 --> 01:54:25.190
And Norfolk State University
was underfunded according

01:54:25.190 --> 01:54:31.900
to the Virginia governmental
formula for 75 years.

01:54:31.900 --> 01:54:33.590
For 75 years.

01:54:33.590 --> 01:54:38.210
And Virginia settled that
underfunding for $10 million,

01:54:38.210 --> 01:54:41.480
for 75 years of underfunding.

01:54:41.480 --> 01:54:44.130
What can you do with
$10 million?

01:54:44.130 --> 01:54:48.750
And I'm not talking about
$10 million in 1870 money.

01:54:48.750 --> 01:54:52.730
I'm talking about $10
million in the latter part

01:54:52.730 --> 01:54:54.300
of the 20th century dollars.

01:54:54.300 --> 01:54:58.970
You can't even construct part
of a building with $10 million.

01:54:58.970 --> 01:55:04.490
So reparations to me has been
seen when it comes to people

01:55:04.490 --> 01:55:06.650
of color as a giveaway.

01:55:06.650 --> 01:55:08.380
That everybody would get a dime.

01:55:08.380 --> 01:55:11.630
But that is not what
reparations is all about.

01:55:11.630 --> 01:55:15.240
It is restoring what was taken,

01:55:15.240 --> 01:55:20.480
what was forcefully
illegally taken.

01:55:20.480 --> 01:55:24.530
And how you restore is really,

01:55:24.530 --> 01:55:27.530
really should be the
discussion line, not whether

01:55:27.530 --> 01:55:30.490
or not it should be
restored but how.

01:55:30.490 --> 01:55:35.360
And the way in which it can be
restored can help really enhance

01:55:35.360 --> 01:55:38.510
our nation.

01:55:38.510 --> 01:55:44.040
[ Applause ]

01:55:44.040 --> 01:55:45.340
